On March 6, he was arrested while he is guarding his Ward as a night watch and later charged under the Penal Code 505 A. He was suffering from diabetes and died from not receiving sufficient medical treatment while in prison.

Pyay Thein, who was arrested while protesting in Ye Township, Mon State on March 22, was charged under Section 505 A of the Penal Code and detained at Kyaikmaraw Prison. He died on August 4 in prison. Even though police said he died from diabetes, Pyay Thein had never suffered from diabetes according to his family and a close friend.

Myint Wai, living in Thanlyin Township in Yangon Region, who was arrested on March 29 and charged under Section 505 A of the Penal Code, contracted COVID-19 in Insein Prison and died inside the prison in July.

A private boarding school principal from Myo Thit Township in Magway Region with pre-existing health conditions, he was arrested on March 23 and charged under Section 505 A of the Penal Code then detained at the Magway Prison. He died from being forced to sit in a stress position (called “Pon Zan”) while he appeared before the court in Magway Prison on May 21.
He was arrested on June 3. He died due to lack of adequate medical attention.

Doctor Maung Maung Nyein Tun, lecturer of surgery of the University of Medicine of Mandalay, who is participating in the Civil Disobedience Movement (CDM), was arrested on June 13 and sued three counts of charges, died on August 8 at Mandalay General Hospital due to COVID-19. He contracted COVID-19 while detained in the Interrogation Center of Mandalay Nandwin. At first, the terrorist junta did not transfer him to the hospital and detained him at the No.9 police station for two weeks. He was transferred to the Mandalay General Hospital only when his condition got worse as he did not receive sufficient medical treatment in the cell.

Moe Thu (aka) Moe Thuzar Htwe, a resident from Kayan Township, Yangon Region, was arrested on June 15. She was charged under Section 505 A of the Penal Code. She caught COVID-19 in prison and died on July 22, due to insufficient medical treatment.

Aye Hla, Vice Chairman of NLD of Kyauktaga Township of Bago Region, died on July 19 at Daik-u (Kyaik Za Kaw) Prison due to injuries consistent with torture during interrogation. He was arrested on June 16 having been accused of providing training to PDFs and allegedly in possession of weapons, as the junta did not find his son Linn Linn Kyaw, MP for Kyauktaga Township of Bago Region.

Maung Htay from Kywe Chan Village in Myingyan Township in Mandalay Region, who was arrested on July 10 allegedly because he was keeping youth protesters and charged under Section 505 A of the Penal Code, died in Myingyan Prison on August 9. According to a friend of his family member, although the Prisons Department said Maung Htay died due to atherosclerosis and hypertension, his body was covered and they were only allowed to look at the face.
On July 14, he died while receiving medical treatment at an Insein prison hospital.

Nyan Win, NLD Secretary, who contracted COVID-19 while he was detained in Insein Prison, and only transferred to Yangon General Hospital due to his severe condition because he did not receive adequate medical treatment in prison, died on July 20 in the hospital.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: Win Kyaing, NLD executive member of Western Hlaingtharya Township of Yangon Region, died on July 20 due to COVID-19 having been detained in Insein Prison.

Nyunt Shwe, MP of Bago Region Hluttaw in constituency No. (1) of Bago Township and also executive committee chairman of the NLD in Bago Township, contracted COVID-19 in prison and died in the early morning of August 16 from the disease while at Bago Hospital receiving medical treatment. Nyunt Shwe had been charged under Section 505 A of the Penal Code and was detained in Bago Prison.

Khun Bwar Hto Thway, NLD member of Hsihseng Township in Shan State, who has been detained since February, contracted COVID-19 while in Nyaungshwe Prison. Khun Bwar Hto Thway died while receiving medical treatment at Sao San Tun Hospital in Taunggyi on August 27.

Myo Naing, living in Ward (3) in Magway Region’s Pakokku Town, was arrested on October 25 for being accused of having relations with the People's Defence Forces (PDFs) in Pakokku Township. Myo Naing died in Pakokku Prison on December 27 from injuries consistent with torture at an interrogation center.

On October 25, 2021, he was arrested at his home. He was sent to Insein Prison on November 9, 2021. At 2 pm on January 1, 2022, he was transferred from the prison hospital to Insein Hospital, due to shortness of breath. He died at 4 pm the same day.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: Aung Aung, from Mingalartaungnyunt Township  in Yangon Region, died at Insein Prison on February 6, 2022. He had been detained in March 2021 and charged under Penal Code 505(a). The prison hospital stated he died of drug-resistant TB but, according to his family, his body presented bleeding from the mouth and nose. Aung Aung was beaten during his arrest and again during solitary confinement in the prison. His family members believe he died from those provoked injuries.

On February 17, at 11 pm, Shwe Yoon Eain, the two-year-old daughter of detainee Nyein Ei Phyo Kyaw, died in Thandwe Prison where she was being held with her mother. Shwe Yoon Eain was a child with poor health who had undergone surgery before. She died of poor health worsened by prison conditions. Her mother, Nyein Ei Phyo Kyaw, was detained under the Counter-Terrorism Law in Thandwe Township, Rakhine State.

Salai Shalom Shan Thang Lian (aka Van Dane) was arrested in June, 2021, in Kale Township and remained under detention in the abovementioned prison.

Kyaw Min, who was sentenced to one and a half year of imprisonment under Section 505 A of the Penal Code at Hpakant Prion, died on May 28, at around 11 PM. He was given heart medication at Lone Khin Area Hospital after experiencing cardiac arrest, and was then urgently transferred to Hpakant Hospital where he died. He had been arrested on December 20, 2021 while protesting in Hpakant Township in Kachin State and was sentenced in late March 2022.

Police flights from peaceful protests in Nay Pyi Taw near Tha Pyay Gone Roundabout Rubber bullets; four people were injured in the crackdown. Among them was 21-year-old Mya Thwet Thwet Khaing, who was shot in the head and taken to a 1,000-bed hospital in Nay Pyi Taw. Even though the junta has stated that security forces do not use lethal weapons, a police officer was seen holding a BA-94 or BA-93 sub-machine gun similar to a Burmese-made Uzi.  A doctor at Nay Pyi Taw Hospital who treated her said the bullet had penetrated her head and most of her brain has ceased functioning. The wound was caused by a live bullet which pierced the back of the right ear and landed on the left side of the head. He was medically diagnosed with brain death. According to a photo, her motorcycle helmet was struck by a bullet, the bullet appeared to have pierced the helmet and it could not have been a rubber bullet. Forensic experts thus have speculated that the bullet may have been a real bullet. She also concluded that the shape of her fall had been a direct hit, not a ricochet. On February 15, the family agreed to remove the breathing tube and transport the body, but the junta verbally pressured them to delay as much as they could. She died at 11:15 a.m. on February 19.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: Monywa is one of the top cities to fight against the military dictatorship since the February 1 military coup. Myint Myint Zin was one of thousands of people in Monywa who took to the streets to protest. Myint Myint Zin, a school teacher and poet who wrote under the pen name Kyi Lin Aye, was active in the daily protests from morning to evening, and at night she was a watchman for the neighborhood; doing her part in the uprising. Myint Myint Zin, who used to say that she did not want any gifts on her upcoming birthday, just wanted democracy. While she was in Monywa just days before her birthday, protesting near Phayar Ni Pagoda on Pyi Daung Su Road, Myint Myint Zin was shot in the chest by the military; killing her.

cellValuesByColumnId.fld7KLBHB6DdATjnu: U Puu Jay Nhun Htan  (J Ngunthang)
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: Arr Khu is a women's rights activist who has been active during the Spring Revolution. At noon on March 28, the armed wing of the Junta cracked down on Tahan protesters with sound grenades, rubber bullets, assault rifles and heavy explosive weaponry.  Arr Khu was providing medical assistance to front line protesters who were injured. A plain clothed junta soldier shot Arr Khu in the chest from a tall building. She died on the way to the hospital. On the return of Arr Khu's body to Chin State, the junta was conducting a search operation in Kalemyo Township and at the exit gates of Kalemyo. Her body was stopped three times on the way back to Chin State. They falsely claimed that the body was not Arr Khu, but the body of someone that had died as a result of hypertension. The junta have regularly taken bodies away and cremated them, themselves. Arr Khu’s family members decided not to use the name "Arr Ku", to prevent this from happening and avoid harassment from the junta.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: A woman active in helping the CDM movement was detained. Due to her testimony, Khant Ko Ko Maung, a CDM policeman from the traffic police force in Chanayethazan Township in Mandalay Region, who was evading arrest in Kyi Kone Village, Patheingyi Township, was shot dead from behind. He was killed on the evening of July 10 when the terrorist junta opened fire while arresting him.
Phoe Sal died due to beatings consistent with torture on July 10 after his arrest by the junta on July 10 while he was searching for oxygen to help treat COVID-19 at Thongwa Township, Yangon Region.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ငမ်ကျင်ပေါင်
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: Two teenagers were shot dead on the spot, three were arrested and one man who is to escape when the terrorist junta opened fire on the six teenagers from Naung Ka Thit Village in Sub-MyoThit Township, Tamu District, Sagaing Region who were returning home from visiting a nearby Village at 10 pm on July 10. One of the three arrested teenagers was shot in the stomach and released on July 12. The two others were tortured to death in detention. The four fallen teenagers were Ngam Chin Pso, 23 years old, Dou Kho Lel, 16 years old, Mang Gou, 17 years old, and Pao Gin Mang, 18 years old. The bodies were not returned to the families.

Locals from nearby Villages including Zin Kalal Village in Sagaing Region’s Mingin Township are fleeing as the terrorist junta raids on Villages. San Win from Zin Kalal Village, one of the Villagers fleeing, was killed by the junta while he was returning to the Village to bring rice on July 11. According to a local, his hands were placed behind his back and there were injuries on his face and head from beatings consistent with torture. In addition to this, Myint Swe from Than Pauk Village in Mingin Township was killed by the terrorist junta on July 13.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On July 12, Lun Maung, a local palm farmer from Thayet Pin Village in Seikphyu Township in Magway Region, was shot dead unprovoked by local junta police.

Locals from nearby Villages including Zin Kalal Village in Sagaing Region’s Mingin Township are fleeing as the terrorist junta raids on Villages. Myint Swe from Than Pauk Village in Mingin Township was killed by the terrorist junta on July 13.
Sithu, 16 years old, was shot dead as the terrorist junta opened fire into the crowd arguing among each other in Pyigyitagon Township, Mandalay Region on July 14.

On July 14, Ma Khaw Roi from Num Lang Village in Momauk Township, Kachin State, was raped and killed by three junta soldiers, while she was on the way to a field. Three of the perpetrators are from Division 88. On July 19, junta personnel from a light infantry battalion and Division 88, met with the victim’s family in Num Lang Village and gave them 2.1M kyat ($1,276) in compensation, stating that lawful action would be taken against the three soldiers.
On July 16, the terrorist junta raided nearby Villages including Inpinhla Village in Sagaing Region’s Minkgin Township and shot Zwe Ko Ko from Inpinhla Village to death.

On the morning of July 16, Tin Ohn from Ayekayit Village in Magway Region’s Sinbaungwe Township was shot over 15 times by the terrorist junta and died while he was working at a sesame field when the junta did not find his son Yan Myo Aung, MP of No (1) Constituency of Sinbaungwe Township of Magway Region, who was evading arrest because he did not sign to not support CRPH and NUG.

On the night of July 17, junta troops raided Seik Khun Village in Sagaing Region’s Shwebo Township and shot four youths to death unprovoked while they were guarding the Village. These youths are Thet Soe, Htay Hlaing Win, Aung Paing Htwe and Aung Hein Kyaw.

In the night of July 17, junta troops raided Seik Khun Village in Sagaing Region’s Shwebo Township and shot four youths to death unprovoked while they were guarding the Village. These youths are Thet Soe, Htay Hlaing Win, Aung Paing Htwe and Aung Hein Kyaw.

On July 17, a terrorist junta set up a camp at Doe Nwel Village in Sagaing Region’s Kale Township and shot Kyaw Aung,  unnamed youth, Maung Maung Aye, Hlay Lwin and 15-year-old Thar Pha to death. These five Villagers were not fleeing when the military entered the Village.

On the night of July 18, Ka Lal from Kin Mone Chong Village in Htantabin Township, Bago Region, who was actively involved in protests, was killed at her home, by three junta personnel. Her daughter, who is a 7th-grade student, also received life-threatening injuries.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: သိန်းတင့် (ခ) ဂျစ်လိပ်
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On July 21, terrorist junta’s troops raided Kun Seik Village in Sagaing Region’s Shwebo Township and shot dead local Villager Thein Tint (aka) Jit Leik, when he was running away in fear.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: အောင်ပိုင်
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: Aung Paing, a motorbike taxi driver and local Villager from Sin Phyu Kyun Village in Mon State’s Thaton Township, was shot dead when he was among a group of motorbike taxi drivers who ran away in fear when they saw the terrorist junta’s troops entered Sin Phyu Kyun Village and start shooting. The body of Aung Paing was not returned to his family.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ကုလား (ခ) တင်မင်းထွဋ်
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: Tin Min Htut (aka) Kalar, was shot dead by the junta with another man managing to escape. On July 25 at Pyay Town in Bago Region while Tin Min Htut was riding a motorbike with the other man on the back seat when they did not stop when demanded.

12 men who were arrested by terrorist junta’s troops on July 26 and July 27 in Sagaing Region’s Kani Township, were later found killed with injuries consistent with torture. These men included three men from Kani Town, seven men including a 14-year-old child from Thayet Taw Village, and two men from Kho Twin Village. Their bodies were found in the forest near East Taung Pauk Village in Kani Township on July 31.

On July 27, at around noon, plain-clothed junta personnel shot Thu Thu Zin dead in the head. She died on the spot. This occurred during a Mya Taung protest at the east shrine entrance of the Mahamuni Pagoda in Mandalay Region.

Myo Chit, a member of Mingin PDF of Sagaing Region’s Mingin Township, who was trapped and arrested along with over 50 members of Mingin PDF on July 28 at Taung Phyu Village in Sagaing Region’s Mingin Township, was killed on August 3 in an interrogation center in Kale Town.

After clashes between KIA and Infantry Battalion #58 who were in Madein Village and Laban Village in Kachin State’s Waingmaw Township on the night of July 29, Aong Li, a worker, died due to an artillery shell fired by Infantry Battalion #58, which exploded at the company’s compound in Laban Village. One other company worker was seriously injured.

On July 29, two Civilians named Min Htike and Naing Min from Thit Nyi Naung Village in Magway Region’s Pauk Township died when they stepped on a mine set by junta troops at Kyeenygo Mountain in Pauk Township.

On July 29, two Civilians named Min Htike and Naing Min from Thit Nyi Naung Village in Magway Region’s Pauk Township died when they stepped on a mine set by junta troops at Kyeenygo Mountain in Pauk Township.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: လန်ခန့်ထန်
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: Lam Khant Htan and Lar Kein from Thar Yar Kone Village in Sagaing Region’s Kale Township were arrested on July 30 on suspicion over weapons allegedly found in a private car they were passengers in when they arrived at the entrance of Kale Town returning home from work in China. His family was informed on July 31 that Lam Khant Htan died due to COVID-19. However, his leg and hand were broken, with many injuries to the head, back, leg and neck. Lar Kein who was detained along with Lam Khant Htan is still being detained.

Moe Kyaw, a local Villager from See-Din-Yan Village in Kachin State’s Mogaung Township, died from an injury to the head from an artillery shell fired by the junta’s artillery battalion based near Mogaung Town after clashes between KIA and the junta on the early morning of July 31 at  See-Din-Yan Village which is located west of Namti Town in Mogaung Township.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldHfL2UA8oU0Imne: Sai Ye Yint (aka) Myo Chit Thu
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: Sai Ye Yint (aka) Myo Chit Thu, who was shot in the groin and detained when the junta raided a home where youth protesters were staying in Patheingyi Township, Mandalay Region in the morning of July 31, died that same morning. The body was not returned to his family.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: မောင်မြင့်
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: Maung Myint had a mental breakdown due to the killings and violence in Kani Township and drove a motorbike to Kani Town which is four miles away from Kho Twin Village. When he arrived, he shouted that “our Civilians were killed because of you” and went close to the school wall of B.E.H.S in Kani Town where the junta’s soldiers had set up a base. Junta soldiers shot dead the unarmed Maung Myint. His family said the body was disposed by the junta troops that night.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: လှိုင်ဝေဦး
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On August 5, junta soldiers and the Pyu Saw Htee detained five Than Pauk Villagers near Obo Village in Sagaing Region’s Mingin Township allegedly for being involved in the anti-coup revolution. Hlaing Wai Oo was beaten to death right in front of the detained persons at a school in Pan Sat Village. Two sons had taken their mother to Yar Village which is close to Pan Sat Village because she was suffering from illness. A total of five people including two sons and their mother and two other men were arrested while returning together. Hlaing Wai Oo was killed in front of his mother. A few days later, three of the Villagers were released, but nothing has yet been heard about the one remaining Villager.

A family was informed that Hsann Win from Tha Pyay Kone Village in Ayeyarwady Region’s Myanaung Township, who was arrested by Tha Pyay Kone Village Police Station in the morning of August 7 for questioning, died at the hospital at 2 pm that day due to severe injuries. There were beatings all over his body consistent with torture. Win Tun and Aung Myint Oo from Tha Pyay Kone Village were arrested with him and were released the same day. On the morning of August 9, local police Kyaw Kyaw Maung and a person wearing plain clothes came to his family to settle the case for 3 million kyats. His family members will not accept this negotiation.

On the afternoon of August 9, three junta police wearing plainclothes entered Pike Thin Village and opened fire because a protest leader San Ko from Pike Thin Village escaped from arrest when three junta police tried to arrest him at a COVID-19 checkpoint. Aung Zaya, a Villager from Pike Thin Village in Magway Region’s Myaing Township, was dragged into their car because he was holding a slingshot when he went out of the house to look. When junta police arrived near a pond at the top of the Village, they told Aung Zaya to get out of the car and told him to run towards the pond. While Aung Zaya was running, they shot him from his back. Aung Zaya died on the spot from this gunshot injury.
On the morning of August 10, Pi Ngeih Tlinng was shot dead in the chest, at home in Falam Township, Chin State. This happened during an unprovoked shooting by junta soldiers.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ဝေဝေမြင့် (ခ) ပန်းသီး
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On August 10, on 44th Street in Botahtaung Township, Yangon Region, the junta raided an apartment. One out of the five youths, Wai Wai Myint (aka) Pann Thee, jumped off from the apartment and died on the spot.
Wai Zaw Phyo, one out of five youths who jumped off from the apartment on August 10, died during the apartment raid by the terrorist junta on 44th Street in Botahtaung Township, Yangon.

On the night of August 10, the junta’s troops raided Kyi Kone Village in Sagaing Region’s Myaung Township and arrested and beat a local Villager called Nyi Nyi Latt for no reason. The junta soldiers shot him to death when he then ran away. The body of Nyi Nyi Latt was found in a port in the Village with many injuries on his body, and gunshot injuries to the neck and head, according to locals.

A Civilian named Aung Yu from Dawei Township in Tanintharyi Region, who was arrested on the night of August 11, died on August 14, three days after his arrest. His wife was informed that Aung Yu died due to COVID-19, but his wife has denied that her husband caught the disease.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: အမည်စုံစမ်းဆဲ
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On the morning of August 12 in Myingyan Township, Mandalay Region the armed wing of the Junta opened fire on three youths who were on motorbikes. A young girl from a house near the shooting, who is around one year old, was shot in the head and stomach and died on the spot. In addition, Nyein Chan, the father of the child, was shot twice in the arm and the mother was shot in the leg.
On August 12, Joshua from Parmun Chaung Village in Falam Township, Chin State, was arrested by the terrorist junta’s troops, and shot dead in the back of the head.

Junta troops raided Pa Linne, Gonetan and Kantha Villages in Sagaing Region’s Shwebo Township, then arrested and shot dead a local from Gonetan Village called Nan, on August 12. The incident happened at a school in Pa Linne Village, where they had set up a camp, after they failed to get any answer from Nan.

Hla Myint Oo, living in Thapyay Yay Village in Pauk Township, Magway Region, who had opened a shop, was shot with a flintlock (traditional hunting) rifle used by junta troops on the evening of August 13. The junta then set a bomb on an old motorbike in front of his shop.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: Lang Myaw (လန်းမျော်)
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On the evening of August 13, a resident from Wuyan village named Lang Myaw and her husband, were shot in front of infantry battalion #58, while they were passing by on a motorbike, after returning from shopping in Waingmaw. Lang Myaw was shot on her left side, into her ribs, and the bullet went through her exiting at her right ribs. She died at the Waingmaw Hospital while receiving medical treatment.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ဟန်ဇော်ထွန်း (ခ) တုတ်ပြဲ
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: Han Zaw Tun (aka) Toke Pye who suffers from mental illness and lives in Pa Dan Village, was beaten by the terrorist junta’s appointed night guards and died on the spot. The incident happened in front of the Ward (20) administrator's office in Hlaingthaya Township in Yangon Region at 2:30 am on August 13 while Han Zaw Tun (aka) Toke Pye was returning from his mother’s home.

On the night of August 14, a young man playing a game on a bench in front of a shop panicked and ran into the house in front of him when he saw a junta soldier patrol in Hpayargyi Town, Bago Township, Bago Region. The other young man in that house named Ye Htet Ko was shot dead in his left chest as the junta troops opened fire into the house with the door closed.

Than Sein, a local Villager from Kyauk Sauk Kalay Village in Kyaukse Township, Mandalay Region, who was arrested by the terrorist junta’s troop around 10 am on August 15, died on the morning of August 16 due to severe beatings. Three of his teeth fell out due to the punching, and beating with wire and bamboo sticks because Than Sein did not unlock his phone. Than Sein was beaten this way until in the evening, according to locals. Than Sein was actively involved in his community and went into hiding after the terrorist junta came to search and arrest NLD supporters. He was arrested because a junta-appointed administrator informed the troops when he arrived home from hiding.

Terrorist junta’s troops raided Kyauk Khel Tat Village in Sagaing Region’s Mingin Township and arrested three Villagers named Bo Aung, Chit Lwin and Phoe Toke on August 16. They killed these three Villagers on August 17 and disposed the bodies in Chindwin River.

Thet Moe died on the spot and Moe was shot in her arm.

On the night of September 10 at Tamu Township in Sagaing Region, a civilian named Rar Jar was arrested when he ran into junta soldiers who were patrolling the streets, while he was returning home from his friend’s house. On September 11, his body was found by locals and there were gunshot wounds and injuries consistent with torture, on his body.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: The armed wing of the junta arrested the cycle mechanic, Tun Myint Naing on September 11, who was living in Kan Thit Village in Sagaing Region’s Khin-u Township. He was shot dead in his head and back on the roadside, after being questioned and tortured. Tun Myint Naing was at his workshop when he was arrested.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On the night of September 11 at Yangon’s Region’s Dagon Myothit (North) Township, Aung Ko Lwin died and a woman got injured in her leg and stomach, when the terrorist military followed them with a military vehicle. The terrorist military shot the car driven by Aung Ko Lwin, as he did not stop when they told him to. The woman was in serious condition.

On September 11, the terrorist junta troops raided and set up a camp at Hmwae Lal Village in Sagaing Region’s Gangaw Township and arrested three locals named Oo Thu, Maung Shwe and a man suffering from mental illness. On September 13, the bodies of Oo Thu and Maung Shwe were found with bruises and gunshot injuries in the stomach. The body of the mentally ill man was found on September 14 and was found to have knife cuts on his neck and stabbing on his chest, and his private parts had been cut off.

Than Aye; the NLD Party member of Waw Township in Bago Region, living in Letpan Thone Pin Village in Waw Township, was arrested on September 13 and died the same day, due to torture during interrogation. His body was cremated by the terrorist junta on September 14, without informing the family.

Naing Linn, an executive member of the NLD party of Salin Township in Magway Region, died when he arrived at the hospital. He was shot many times by the terrorist junta police, while he was at home in Khin Palu Village in Wunra Village Tract in Salin Township, on the evening of September 14.

On the night of September 14, ten junta soldiers, wearing plainclothes, raided Taung Bet Village in Pauk Township, Magway Region and arrested Sandar Win. Sandar Win is the accountant for the People's Defence Force. The junta stole 18 million Kyat from her. She was then shot dead at close range, in the back of the head.

Kyaw Min Oo, from Sagaing Region’s Kale Township, was tortured to death during interrogation, after he was arrested on September 14. On September 18, his family was informed that he had died. His body was not returned to his family by the terrorist junta.

On September 17, Soe Maung Maung, who was detained by the military junta in Myingyan Township in Mandalay Region, died three days after being arrested. Six youths, including Soe Maung Maung, were arrested by junta soldiers in Myingyan on September 14, being accused of making weapons.

Thein Soe Aung, living in Letpadan Township in Bago Region, who was arrested on September 16, died on September 17 due to torture, bruises were found on his body. In Bagon Region’s Monyo Township, the home of a junta-appointed village administrator was shot at, and his personal aide was killed, and the junta administrator's son injured. Approximately 30 locals including Thein Soe Aung and his wife were arrested during this incident.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On the night of September 17, a 16-year-old child named Yin Min Khant (aka) Pin Att, living in Kadat Nge Htein Village in Launglon Township in  Tanintharyi Region, was shot to death by terrorist junta soldiers, who set up a camp at the village monastery.

On September 17 around 9 pm, Aung Than Zaw, who is a primary school teacher living in Myo Lulin Village in Magway Region’s Myothit Township, and a 15-year-old boy were stopped, beaten and questioned by junta soldiers who were guarding Myanmar military-owned Telecom Tower in that village while they were going to a petrol station at the top of the village. Then, Aung Than Zaw was shot in his neck at close range and seriously injured. Aung Than Zaw was sent to the Myothit Hospital and died while being transferred to the 1000-bed Hospital in Nay Pyi Taw on the morning of September 18.

On September 17 around 10:30 pm, Kyaw Kyaw from Taungdwingyi Town in Magway Region was arrested while driving his motorbike to see an ill relative, and tortured overnight. On September 18, his family was informed to collect Kyaw Kyaw. When his family came to get him, he was still alive but he was not able to move. Therefore, he was sent to Magway Hospital but died at the hospital on the same day.

Soe Min Oo (aka) Paw Kyaung was shot dead in his temple, when the terrorist junta troops raided Sipin Gyi (aka) Let Pan Khone Village on September 18 in Sagaing Region’s Kale Township due to a killed junta informer. In addition to this, a man, whose name is still unconfirmed, was shot dead while driving into the village.

On the evening of September 18, Pastor Cung Biak Hmun from Thantlang Centenary Baptist Church was shot dead while going to put out a fire caused by the junta’s artillery shells, in Htantalang Town, Chin State. In addition to this, terrorist junta troops took Pastor Cung Biak Hmun’s wrist watch and phone and cut off his finger and took his wedding ring.

Around midnight on September 20, terrorist junta soldiers raided Shaw Phyu (Middle) Village in Natogyi Township in Mandalay Region, by continuously opening fire. The home of NLD supporters was shot at during the raid, and five family members, including a one and half year old child, were shot. Four of five were shot dead on the spot. The one and half year old child died, due to a thigh injury, when he arrived at Mandalay General Hospital. These five family members are Bo Khin, 76 years old, Than, 75 years old, Maung Tun, 50 years old, Maw Htay, 30 years old and Zwe Htet Maw, one and a half years old.

Ye Yint, who was detained at the No.7 Police Station in Mahaaungmyay Township in Mandalay Region, was shot dead by police after being accused of running away while he was leaving the police station, when he was released on the evening of September 24. On September 22, he was arrested on suspicion of setting off a bomb explosion in Sein Pan Ward.

They were shot dead by terrorist junta troops, while they were arriving in Daw Kha Light Lin Football Ground.

Pauk Gyi was killed on the embankment of Sein Pan. The body was found with a gunshot wound to his head and stab wounds on his neck.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: Sithu Kaung Myat, a political activist from Bago City in Bago Region, had gunshot wounds on his head, stomach and hands, when junta police shot him while arresting him at home, on September 23 at around 10 pm. He died on the afternoon of September 24, while he was receiving medical treatment in Bago General Hospital. About one hour after he died, police sealed the house where he and his mother lived, so that no one could enter.

On October 30, villagers who were farming in the forest ran away in fear, during a search by terrorist junta soldiers. The junta searched the forest, after they raided Ingottor Village in Kanbalu Township, Sagaing Region, nearby. The soldiers shot dead a local villager, Thein Min, in the back.

Three brothers named Phyo Wai Tun, Hphone Wai Tun and Show Wai Tun were arrested by the Infantry Battalion 13 based in Chauk Township, on the night of October 31, for being accused of supporting People's Defence Force (PDF). Phyo Wai Tun’s family was informed to retrieve his body on November 1.

Two civilians were shot dead by soldiers stationed at Dala Police Station and Dala Township Hall after a bomb exploded near a municipal office which is located Dala-Twantay Roadside on October 31 around 8:30 pm. The names of these two civilians are Soe Ko and his friend Ousaman and one was shot dead in the stomach and one other was shot five times to death when he screamed with bullet wound. They were shot when they passed near that incident place by motorbike.

On the night of November 7, soldiers from the armed wing of the Junta raided Pauk Pin Village in Monywa Township, Sagaing Region. The soldiers entered the wrong house, and shot dead Mya Lay Nwe in the chest and neck, while she was running away in fear.

Ye Naing Aung (aka) Ko Ye was selling electronics, Mont Hnin Khar and fried rice in Natt Village, Htantabin Township, Bago Region. He was arrested on suspicion, 30 minutes after a bomb explosion at the village administrator’s office in Natt Village on November 8.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: Chit Hsann Maung, a civilian living in No (5) South Bayint Naung Ward in Madaya Township, Mandalay Region, was killed due to beatings consistent with torture. He was killed after being arrested by the police from Madaya Police Station on November 8.

On November 10 at around 10 pm, terrorist junta troops arrived at Sa Khan Ma Village in Natmauk Township, Magway Region, and opened fire while youths were playing a game at the top of the village. A youth named Wai Thu Aung was shot dead in his chest and leg and another named Hein Myat Thu was beaten and arrested.

On November 11 at around 3 am, junta troops from infantry battalion 285 opened fire in the neighborhood. Wai Linn Thu who was working in a rubber field in Jat Gar Village in Palaw Township, Tanintharyi Region, was shot dead.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On November 11, terrorist junta troops raided Aung Si Myay Village in Sagaing Region’s Tabayin Township and arrested a local called Thein Htike and took him to the forest which is located south of the village. The troops placed his hands on back and shot him dead in the back of his head at close range.
On November 11, Kyaw Min Htay (aka) Khin Nyunt, living in Aung Thiri Ward in Khin-U Township, Sagaing Region, was shot dead, while traveling from Khin-U Town to Zee Kone Village by motorbike.

On the morning of November 13, the family of Ye Aung was informed to retrieve his body. Ye Aung was arrested as a hostage on the evening of November 12 at Kyauktada Village in Madaya Township, Mandalay Region. Myint Naing and Ye Aung are the father and uncle of a youth, who was issued a warrant under Section 505 A of the Penal Code and were arrested as hostages, when the junta did not find the youth. Ye Aung was killed during interrogation and many injuries consistent with torture, were found on his head.

On the morning of November 13, terrorist junta troops raided Mayaninn Village in Khin-U Township, Sagaing Region and opened fire. Thar Aye, living in Mayaninn Village, was reaping grass for his cows at the top of the village, when he was shot dead in the stomach, due to the unprovoked shooting.

On November 17, Nyi Khin, who helped IDPs in Pekon Township, Shan State, was killed during interrogation at 7th Military Operations Command (MOC-7), due to injuries consistent with torture. Nyi Khin was arrested by the terrorist junta and detained at MOC-7 on November 15.

He was arrested by the terrorist junta, along with another civilian, at around 11:30 am that day, being accused of having association with the People's Defence Force (PDF).

These three villagers are Shine Htet Zaw, who is 15 years old, a nine-grade student, Min Zaw Oo, and a woman. Shine Htet Zaw died when he went to put out a fire at a house in the village, caused by terrorist junta troops. He was shot by the junta and died due to excessive bleeding.

They lived in East Kyee Kone Village in Chaung-U Township, Sagaing Region and were shot near the football ground in Khin Mon Village, while they were returning to Kyee Kone Village from Chaung-U Town.

When the junta left on November 22, villagers returned and found the body of the local, Maung Maung Htwe, who had injuries consistent with torture and gunshot wounds. Stab wounds were also found on his ankles.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: Bhone Myint Aung, living in Botahtaung Township, Yangon Region, was killed during interrogation on November 23, after he was arrested on the evening of November 22. Htin Win, father of Bhone Myint Aung, was arrested with his son and released on the night of November 22.

On November 23, Min Naing, living in Thalalbar Village in Ayadaw Township, Sagaing Region, was shot dead by junta soldiers and the Pyu Saw Htee at the bank of the river near Kyauk Kone Village. He was accused of jumping into Mu River and running away, resulting in his death. He was arrested at the shop that he owned on the morning of November 23, for participating in a previous NLD campaign.

He was visiting Indawyoe Village in Taze Township and was killed by the armed wing of the Junta on his way back to Yangon via the bus station.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On the night of November 27, Sithu Kyaw, living in North Okkalapa Township, Yangon Region, was shot dead in the head when he reached to Pazundaung township by the armed wing of the Junta. He was killed whilst driving for personal matters.

Ye Thu Naing, Deputy Officer of Cooperatives Department of Madaya Township, Mandalay Region, who is involved in the Civil Disobedience Movement (CDM), was killed after he was arrested on November 19 at around 9 pm. He had been evading arrest and returned to Madaya as his mother was not well. Therefore, he was arrested on Madaya Road on his return.
He was killed during interrogation.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: သန်းထွန်းအောင်
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On November 29, Than Tun Aung, living in Kaimyauk Village in Myingyan Township, Mandalay Region was killed about four hours after his arrest. He died from being beaten by junta police and soldiers.

Sai Mon Zaw, living in Chan Mya Tharsi Ward in Waw Township, Bago Region, died on the morning of November 30 at Swaltaw Specialist Hospital in Bago, while he was receiving medical treatment for injuries consistent with torture during interrogation. Sai Mon Zaw was arrested in April for providing pamphlets during protests that spoke out against the dictatorship. He died after he was released in October.

Salai Lal Ro Mawi was living in Than Phoe Village in Sagaing Region’s Kale Township and was arrested while farming in his bean farm on the east bank of Myittha River. After being used as a human shield he was burned to death alive in Omyay Htoo Village, Kale Township.

On December 7, Hlaing Win died from torture during interrogation.
On the night of December 8, a civilian named Thar Ngal was shot dead by soldiers in Thanbyuzayat Township, Mon State. Thar Ngal was shot while returning home from work by motorbike.

These villagers are Sein Lwin from Kan Htoo Ma Village, Myo Tun from Chaung Sone Village and one other civilian. Their bodies were found on December 8.

He was on the way to Saw Township for his congregational responsibility when he was arrested. After being severely tortured during interrogation, he was transferred to Magway General Hospital on December 8, and died on the morning of December 9.

Phyo Min, living in Tha Htay Kone (aka) Thu Kha Dipa Village in Myaung Township, Sagaing Region was shot dead by a sniper, shot by the armed wing of the Junta at a wayside public resthouse, where he was resting between Sin Chay Yar Village and Shwe Hlan Village in Yesagyo Township, Magway Region on December 10 at 10 am, while he was resting at that resthouse.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On December 12, Liang Line was shot dead on the spot in Mindat Township, Chin State, during an unprovoked shooting by the armed wing of the Junta. She was standing in front of her house when she was shot.

On December 11, Aum Ki, living in Oakpho Village in Kanpetlet Township, Chin State, and a pastor at the Church of Christ, was arrested by the armed wing of the Junta at the Hotel Zone, when he was returning to Oakpho Village. Aum Ki was shot dead in the head on December 12.

In December, Soe Naing, a freelance photographer and graphic designer, was killed during interrogation. He was arrested by the armed wing of the Junta on December 10, while he was taking photos of the silent strike in Latha Township, Yangon Region. Along with Soe Naing, photographer Zaw Tun was also arrested.

Than Myint was Secretary of the Mahar Kuthala Kari Free Funeral Service Association based in Sakhan Gyi Kone Village, Yenant Thar Village Tract in Mandalay Region’s Madaya Township. He was killed on December 13 from injuries consistent with torture. Than Myint’s whole body and head and face were covered in bruises from beatings.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ထွန်းလွင်ဦး
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On December 14, 17-year-old Tun Lwin Oo was shot dead, and Pyae Sone Oo was arrested by the armed wing of the Junta in Shwebo Township, Sagaing Region. Tun Lwin Oo was driving the motorbike, and Pyae Sone Oo was his passenger when they were fired upon because the pair were riding on the same motorbike.

On the afternoon of December 16, Thiha Naing, living in Zayat Kwin Village in Thabeikkyin Township, Mandalay Region, was shot dead on the spot, by the armed wing of the Junta. He had been shopping, and was returning to Kyi Pauk Taw Village by motorbike, when he was shot. Someone who was with him was also injured. They were shot, as they did not stop their motorbike, when the junta wanted to question them.

On December 14, Khun Naung and his wife, living in Htone Gyi Village in Mingin Township, Sagaing Region, were killed as a result of being set on fire, when around 200 soldiers of the armed wing of the Junta, set their house on fire.

On December 19 at around 10 pm, Htay, living in Pathein Township, Ayeyarwady Region, was shot dead in the neck in close range, by junta police. This happened in front of her house.

On December 17, junta helicopters equipped with machine guns fired a series of shots on Hnan Khar Village in Gangaw Township, Magway Region. They raided and stationed themselves in the village with many armed forces. On December 19, nine bodies, including a child, were found. There were two villagers from Hnan Khar Village named Tin Htay and Kyaw Htay, and one local from Zahall Village. There were also six villagers from Mwae Lae Village which is located South of Hnan Khar Village. Tin Htay and Kyaw Htay were shot in the back of the head, while their hands were tied behind their backs.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: Hla Min Maung (aka) La Min Maung, a middle school teacher of Madotpin Village School in Lewe Township, Nay Pyi Taw, who is involved in the Civil Disobedience Movement (CDM), was killed during interrogation on December 21. He was arrested by the armed wing of the Junta, on the night of December 20.

On December 19, at around 7 pm, Soe Hein, living in Nelchar Village in Myingyan Township, Mandalay Region, was shot dead in the chest by seven soldiers from the armed wing of the Junta, a village administrator and two Pyu Saw Htee members, while Soe Hein was at home.

On October 28, 19 villagers were arrested by the armed wing of the Junta in Shan State. Maung Yeo and Soe Tint, were 2 of the arrestees, the pair were killed while in custody by the terrorist Junta. The 17 remaining villagers remain under detention in the No (1) Police Station in Taunggyi Township. A lawsuit was filed against them under Section 52 of the Counter-Terrorism Law. All the villagers were from Shwe Pyi Aye Village in Shan State’s Pekon Township.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On December 24, Thiha (aka) Kan Kyay, living in Nyin Maw Village in Launglon Township in Tanintharyi Region, was shot dead by the armed wing of the junta. Thiha (aka) Kan Kyay suffered from mental illness, and was killed at Launglon-San Hlan Road in Launglon Township.
On December 21 at 10 am, Naw Khee, living in Htaw Kalaw Khee Village in Mon State’s Bilin Township, was shot dead in the head at close range by the terrorist Infantry Battalion 101.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldHfL2UA8oU0Imne: A Sai Kay (aka) Sai Win Aung
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On December 25, A Sai Kay (aka) Sai Win Aung, a poet and editor of the Federal Journal, was hit in the head by an artillery shell fired by the terrorist military near Mae Wah Khee Village. A Sai Kay (aka) Sai Win Aung died on the spot, in Kayin State’s Myawaddy Township where IDPs were fleeing.

On December 26, Aung Bhone Kyaw, a third year student majoring Geology at Yangon University, was detained in Yangon Region’s Tamwe Township. On December 27, Aung Bhone Kyaw had been tortured to death in interrogation.

On December 26, Zaw Oo, a primary school teacher involved in CDM, was shot to dead by the armed wing of the terrorist junta.  Zaw Oo had been staying in Kachin State’s Shwegu Township. He was killed after he was shot in his leg then detained at the entrance of the Hint-on Village. Zaw Oo had been running away from a clash after returning from cutting bamboo for his sister’s wedding.

On the night of December 25, a civilian called Ye Win Zaw (aka) Kalar was detained by four Pyu Saw Htee militiamen and taken to the village school. On December 26, the family of Ye Win Zaw (aka) Kalar living in Lel Thit Village in Mandalay Region’s Myingyan Township, was informed to retrieve his dead body.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ဇင်မင်းထိုက်
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: Philanthropist, Zin Min Htike, living in Bago Region’s Taungoo Township, had an arrest warrant issued against him in July, 2021, as he was accused of being part of the People’s Defence Force (PDF). He was killed during interrogation, on the night of  January 1, 2022. Injuries consistent with torture were found on his body. He had been arrested on January 1, 2022 at around 2 pm, when he was on the way to Oktwin Township.

The middle school teacher named Nyi Nyi Sein, living in Pauk Taw Village in Myaung Township, Sagaing Region, and involved in the Civil Disobedience Movement (CDM), was arrested on December 17, by the armed wing of the Junta. Nyi Nyi Sein was then burnt to death.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: လှမင်းသိန်း
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On the night of January 1, Hla Min Thein, living in Yangon Region’s Tamwe Township, was arrested by the armed wing of the Junta, when they were checking his home for overnight guests. On January 3, he was killed during interrogation. His family was informed of his death on this day.

Thein Soe (aka) Than Soe, who is a member of NLD’s youth working group in Tanungtha Township, Mandalay Region, was killed on the evening of January 3, 2022, due to torture during interrogation. Thein Soe (aka) Than Soe was arrested on December 26, 2021 and was tortured during interrogation, for one week.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On January 2, two local villagers named Maung Myint and Tin Thaung, living in Intaw Village in Ye-U Township, Sagaing Region, were killed by the armed wing of the Junta, by the school. They were then set on fire.

Kyaw Thura, who is one of four who were arrested on the night of January 2 in Kyauk Myaung Town in Sagaing Region’s Shwebo Township, was killed due to torture during interrogation. On the morning of January 3, the armed wing of the Junta informed the family to retrieve his body.

On January 3, two villagers were killed, when the armed wing of the Junta opened fire from a military helicopter in Nyaun Pin Gyi Taw Village and another nearby village, in Wetlet Township, Sagaing Region. They are named Zaw Myo Naung and Hsann Khaing.

On January 5, the armed wing of the Junta shot Zar Linn in the head, in close range, when he was driving around Monywa Township, Sagaing Region.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: အောင်ကိုလတ်
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On January 4 at around 11.30 pm, Aung Ko Latt, a senior clerk at the Ma Hlwa Kone Diesel Factory for Myanmar Railways, who is involved in the Civil Disobedience Movement (CDM), was arrested and beaten. This happened at Ma Hlwa Kone Railway Staff Housing in Yangon Region’s Mingalar Taungnyunt Township. Aung Ko Latt was accused of being a leader of the People’s Defence Force (PDF). On January 5, Aung Ko Latt was killed during interrogation.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ချစ်ကောင်း
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On January 6, a group of villagers were shot by the armed wing of the Junta. These villagers are living in Ywar Taw Village in Sagaing Region's Shwebo Township, and trapping rats to sell, as a living. The junta shot them when they arrived by seven motorbikes at the top of Hnaw Kone Village, located between Khin-U Township and Kan Thit Village. Chit Kaung, who is 12 years old, who was sitting on the back of one motorbike, died as a result.

On January 7 at around 10 am, villagers living in Kin Shae Village in Thayetchaung Township, Tanintharyi Region, ran away, when the armed wing of the Junta opened fire and entered the village. Khant Zin Htwe who is 14 years old, Ye Zaw Htike who is 17 years old, and Aung Thet Phyo, were shot dead while working as masons in the village. Many other locals were injured in the shooting.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On January 6 and 7, 10 civilians, including a 13 year old child, were arrested on Matupi-Hakha Road, between Kee Lun and Lawn Law village in Matupi Township, Chin State. These civilians were taken to the front line by the armed wing of the Junta, and used as human shields. They were killed by the junta on January 8. cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On the morning of January 30, the Junta soldiers arrived by boat to Thit Seint Gyi Village in Wetlet Township, Sagaing Region. They proceeded to raid the village and fired artillery shells, and arrested six civilians named Thura Tun, Ko Ko Linn Maung, Min Min Tun, Myint Aung, Thae Tun Aung and Zaw Min Tun. They were killed after being used as human shields. Their burned bodies were found on February 4 in the field near the village, with hands tied on their back, while villagers were searching for them, after the Junta soldiers left on February 3.

On the morning of February 2, Myint Maw and Aung Naing Htwe, village self-defense team leaders in Kanbulu Township, Sagaing Region, were shot dead by Pyu Saw Htee militia. The Pyu Saw Htee militia had organized a fraudulent meeting with them to sell weapons. When they arrived at the entrance of Kanbula Town, the Pyu Saw Htee militia arrested and then killed them.

On January 25, a Pyu Saw Htee leader identified as Tint, killed three civilians named Tun Win, Kyaw Win and Shan Maw outside Htan Kone Village in Sagaing Region’s Kanbalu Township. Tint had lied to the three individuals that they had been summoned to the police station and instead, took them outside the village and killed them.

On February 3, at around 9am, three villagers, including Phoe Htoo, were killed after the armed wing of the Junta and the Pyu Saw Htee raided Min Taing Pin Village, in Sagaing Region’s Pale Township. Phoe Htoo was from Inn Kan Village but spent most of his time at Min Taing Pin Village. These three villagers were set on fire in front of the timber factory, located west of the village.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: စိုင်းထွန်းထွန်းဝင်း
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On the midnight of February 2, Sai Tun Tun Win was arrested at his home in Tilin Ward in Shan State’s Kyaukme Township by eight personnels including the hundred-household administrator, the armed wing of the Junta and police wearing plainclothes for the accused of relation to the People’s Defence Forces. On February 3, his family inquired about the whereabouts of his detention, the police force told them to meet him at the hospital. At around 9 pm of that day, he died at the Kyaukme hospital due to torture wounds inflicted during interrogation. He presented bruises all over his body and his skull was crushed. His family was coerced by the hundred-household’s administrator to lie about the place of arrest of Sai Tun Tun Win, and say he was captured on the street, while violating the curfew. Sai Tun Tun is an internally displaced person and he fled to Kyaukme due to the clashes that occurred between the ethnic armed organization at Tawt San Village, Kyaukme Township.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: မဂျီဘရန်နန်
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On February 4, Pastor Magi Brang Nan died due to an airstrike deployed by the armed wing of the Junta at Kat Hmaw Village in Hpakant Township, Kachin State. Another three civilians were also injured because of this attack.

On February 7, at around 9 pm, a civilian named Ye Myint and a youth were shot dead by the armed wing of the Junta for going out at night. This crime took place at Garwi Street, Aung San Ward, in Ye-U Township, Sagaing Region.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ပိုင်ဇေရဲထွန်း
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On the afternoon of February 8, the Junta soldiers stationed at Ma Daung Hla Village, in Sagaing Region’s Khin-U Township, and tried to enter and destroy Ma Daung Gyi Village and Shwe Kar Village. They shot Paing Zay Ye Tun and his father, Hla Tun Oo, to death when father and son were at home, near the top of Ma Daung Gyi Village.

On the afternoon of February 8, the Junta soldiers stationed at Ma Daung Hla Village, in Sagaing Region’s Khin-U Township, and tried to enter and destroy Ma Daung Gyi Village and Shwe Kar Village. They shot Paing Zay Ye Tun and his father, Hla Tun Oo, to death when father and son were at home, near the top of Ma Daung Gyi Village.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ကောင်းထက်ပိုင်
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On February 9, 2022, at around 10 am, a civilian named Kaung Htet Paing was shot dead by the military forces for protesting against the Junta in front of a military vehicle, at Bo Hmue Ba Htoo Road, in Yangon Region’s Dagon Myothit (North) Township. As soon as Kaung Htet Paing got off the bus with his mother, and saw the military vehicle, he ran towards it and raised the three fingers salute.

On February 11, Chan Htet, living in Kya Oae Village in Pauk Township, Magway Region, was arrested by the Pyu Saw Htee from Dee Dote Kwin Village, and was shot dead. The killing occurred at the edge of a forest near Aung Chan Thar Village, also known as Wun Lae Yoe Village. Gunshot wounds were found on his head and back. Chan Htet was arrested and killed for entering Dee Dote Kwin village at night while visiting a friend.

On February 7, Hung Ki was killed on the spot after he was hit by an artillery shell fired by the military. The convoy was traveling on the Mindat-Matupi Road, while he was hiding in the valley of Mindat Township, Chin State. The convoy indiscriminately opened fire against the surrounding villages, and the artillery shells exploded where some civilians were hiding.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: စောကလိုစေး
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: Two civilians named Saw Klo Say and Zwe were burned alive at Sanpya Three Mile Pa Kyae Village in Kayah State’s Loikaw Township by the armed wing of the Junta on February 10. They were warehouse guards. The incident took place at the corner of the compound of Saw Klo Say’s house.

Two civilians named Saw Klo Say and Zwe were burned alive at Sanpya Three Mile Pa Kyae Village in Kayah State’s Loikaw Township by the armed wing of the Junta on February 10. They were warehouse guards. The incident took place at the corner of the compound of Saw Klo Say’s house.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: တိန်ယောင်ကိုင်ရာ
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On February 11 at around 11 pm, the military forces shot approximately seven youths while they were passing by a car at Si Tar Pu Ward in Kachin State’s Myitkyina Township. As a result, Tein Yaung Kai Yar, died, a woman was shot on the thigh, and the other youths were arrested. They drove away when the military ordered them to stop.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ဇင်မင်းခိုင်
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On February 14, Zin Min Khaing was repeatedly shot by the Junta soldiers while he was returning home from the farm at Nwar Bann Gyi Village in Shan State’s Ywangan Township. Afterwards, his body was taken away by the soldiers.

Arr Khe Zi Par and Li Jar Dawe, a couple living in Phat Mar Village in Kachin State’s Puta-O township, were shot dead by the armed wing of the Junta while running away by bike from the village due to the clash that occurred on the night of February 15. Arr Khe Zi Par was shot in the chest two times and Li Jar Dawe was shot in the chest one time.

Arr Khe Zi Par and Li Jar Dawe, a couple living in Phat Mar Village in Kachin State’s Puta-O township, were shot dead by the armed wing of the Junta while running away by bike from the village due to the clash that occurred on the night of February 15. Arr Khe Zi Par was shot in the chest two times and Li Jar Dawe was shot in the chest one time.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ဝင်းဖြိဟိန်း
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: They were arrested at the top of the village while running away, when the armed wing of the Junta entered the village on January 30. They were killed after being arrested.
They were arrested at the top of the village while running away, when the armed wing of the Junta entered the village on January 30. They were killed after being arrested.

On the night of February 15, the armed wing of the Junta and Pyu Saw Htee, who were stationed in Nyaung Toe Village school, Myingyan Township, in Mandalay Region, assaulted a civilian called Sann Aung and his two sons, Tun Tun Oo and Than Htike Oo. The attack happened in their home, for the reason of participating in protests against the coup. Sann Aung was sent to the Myingyan District Hospital and Ngazun Hospital where he was also refused treatment. Sann Aung died on February 17 at around 9 pm.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: အောင်ညွန့်
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On the evening of February 17, Aung Nyunt, from Nyaung Toe Village in Myingyan Township, Mandalay Region, was taken to Nyaung Toe Village school and beaten. Later that day, at around 9pm, his body was found at the side of the road.

In the morning of February 19th, junta soldiers and Pyu Saw Htee members raided Pay Lae Village, in Kanbalu Township, Sagaing Region, and attacked with artillery shells. As a result, 3 family members died from the attacks, as they were hiding inside a house at the south of the village. The victims are Than Nwe, her son Chan Nyein Aung and her daughter Phoo Phoo. A civilian named Chit Kaung, from another village, also died in the attack. Further shootings of junta forces also resulted in the death of Thein Zaw, primary income provider of the 3 family members, and a grade-8 student, Hein Ko.

On February 20 at around 2:30 pm, Myo Hlaing was shot on the leg and back by the armed wing of the Junta, while he was sitting on the backseat of the motorbike, at the checkpoint at North of the Ayeyarwady Bridge in Pakokku Township, in Magway Region. Allegedly, the reason of the shooting was that two men were in the same motorbike. Myo Hlaing died due to severe bleeding, as the military did not call an ambulance in time. The driver of the motorbike was arrested.

On February 19, at around 11 am, Khaing Zaw Win, living in Din Paunk Village in Kani Township, Sagaing Region was shot dead by junta soldiers in Chai Village Monastery. When the junta soldiers arrived, he tried to escape on a motorbike, along with other villagers. The junta shot him in the back, killing him.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ဟိန်းဇော်လတ်
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On February 16, around 1 pm, a clash broke out between the armed wing of the Junta and Sayar San-PDF Joint Force, between Popa and Tamar Pin Khwa villages, in Pale Township, Sagaing Region. During the clash, Hein Zaw Lat was arrested by the armed wing of the Junta, when returning to bring a motorbike. He was shot to death in the head.

On February 18, around 9 pm, two civilians named La Par and Htein Nan were shot to death by the Junta soldiers as they did not stop the motorbike in front of the LIB 437 based on Kachin State’s Momauk Township. One was shot in the eye and the other was shot in the mouth and stomach. They died on the spot.

On the morning of February 18, Naw Phu Tin was shot to death by an artillery shell in Kamai Kone village, in Kawkareik Township, Kayin State. The armament was fired by an artillery outpost of IB 97 based in Kawkareik Township. In addition, Naw Phu Tin’s husband and other villagers got injured.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ထက်နေခြည်မင်း
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: Sann Min, Khin Saw, Saw Min Oo and Htet Nay Chi Min were killed by the military column. The later was living in Min Kone Village, in Sagaing Region’s Kawlin Township, and was evading arrest due to her involvement in the Civil Disobedience Movement (CDM). After the military column entered Min Kone Village on February 22, their bodies were found by local villagers at the Taung Phi village’s hill on February 23. Their hands were tied on their back and knife wounds were found on their necks and hands. Htet Nay Chi Min and Khin Saw were raped and killed but is not been independently confirmed.

On the night of 16 February, Tauk Tae was arrested and killed by the armed wing of the Junta. He was a villager from Thit Khal village, in Budalin Township, Sagaing Region. His body showed marks consistent with severe beating.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On February 22, the armed wing of the Junta fired artillery shells in Ngar Phar Village, in Sagaing Region’s Kale Township, during a military operation. Two local villagers, named Aung Tun and Than Hla, were arrested, tortured and killed. Than Hla suffered from muteness. The bodies presented gunshot wounds and other injuries.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: In the morning of February 23, three IDPs fleeing from Cahung Khwa Village, in Sagaing Region’s Kale Township, were killed by Junta soldiers after being arrested at a hut in the farm of Than Pho Village. The victims were Ngun Za Len and her two daughters, Mai Thian Nun Cawi and Mai Ngun Za Thian. Local villagers found their bodies burnt in the farm of East Than Pho Village on February 24.

On February 24 at 9:30 pm, 19-year-old Saw Khu Nae Lar, a local living in Ka Pi Khee Village, in Kayin State’s Hpapun Township, died after being shot in the back. Four other villagers got injured, and five houses were destroyed as Border Guard Force (BGF) Battalion #1013 fired three artillery shells in that village.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On the morning of February 25, the armed wing of the Junta raided and set fire to Hna Ma Sar Yit village, in Sagaing Region’s Shwebo Township. Khin Than died in the fire while she was hiding in the bathroom, as she was not able to run away. Soe Lwin Oo was also unable to flee and burned to death in his house. In addition, Yin Sann Aye and Thein were shot to death while running away with other villagers.

On February 28, the armed wing of the junta attacked Tha Pyay Aye Village in Yinmarbin Township, Sagaing Region, by the airstrike. Aung Min was shot to death while running away in fear.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On the midnight of February 25, Thein Htike Oo, living in Maung Mae Shaung Village in Tanintharyi Region’s Dawei Township, was shot to death by Junta soldiers at the checkpoint in Eain Shae Pyin Village, while he was crossing by motorbike. Thein Htike Oo suffers from mental illness. His body was not returned to his family and was cremated by the military.

On February 28, the armed wing of the Junta and Pyu Saw Htee personnel assaulted villages in Gangaw Township, Magway Region. Seven locals from Shwebo Village were killed. Their names are Thar Nyi, Wai Yan Oo, Pyar Tar Maung (aka) Zin Min Htut, Nyein Chan Maung, Lat Soe, Win Soe and Tun Zaw. Five of the villagers were arrested, hands tied and burned alive, and two others were shot dead.

On March 8, 2022, at around 9 am, Junta troops raided Thein Taw Village, in Sagaing Region’s Khin-U Township. The military fired at least 50 rounds from 40 mm grenade launchers, as they entered the village and clashed with People's Defence Team fighters. The Defence Teams withdraw, after junta troops fired on them uninterruptedly. 11 fighters were detained and shot dead. Signs of torture were present on the bodies, and they had been shot in the head. The 11 fighters from Thayet Pin Wun Village from Shwebo Township, Mhan Taw Village and Thein Taw Village in Khin-U Township. Their bodies were found in the field near Thein Taw Village, Khin-U Township, Sagaing Region.

Nu Nu Win was with Aung Phyo Kyaw on a motorcycle, after buying snacks. Junta soldiers shot the two civilians, as they refused to stop for a check. Nu Nu Win got shot on the neck and died on the spot. Aung Phyo Kyaw was hit in the sternum and remains in serious condition.

On the morning of March 16, the armed wing of the Junta entered Peikkhaya Village, in Sagaing Region's Mingin Township, and opened fire. The military shot to death Thar Chit, who was unable to run away from home.

In addition, Aung Khant Hein, a volunteer for village development, was shot and arrested. He did not receive medical treatment and died during interrogation, on the night of March 20.

On April 9, the junta's troops entered Sat Kant Village, Kale Township, Sagaing Region and began firing indiscriminately. Due to this, Tawk Rem Cer was shot in the neck. Her body was discovered on April 11. She had another relative, her mother, who had been seeking refuge at Tarhan Ward while she had been the only one at home.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ချမ်းမင်းနောင်
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On April 2, Chan Min Naung, the leader of the Che Guevara Guerrillas group, controlled by the Kyauktan People's Defence Force (KPDF), Yangon Region, was arrested by the lackeys of the administrator of San Chain Mi Ward, Kyauktan Township. Chan Min Naung was dragged around by a car from his tied up hands and he was later killed after getting tortured by the junta's intelligence and the ardent junta supports from other wards nearby.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ခိုင်လင်းသူ
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: In the morning of April 12, Khaing Linn Thu from Nat Myaung Village in Kale Township, Sagaing Township, encountered junta soldiers on a patrol near Si Thar Village, while on his way to Kale Town on a motorcycle. The junta troops killed Khaing Linn Thu and subsequently burned his body.

In the afternoon of April 12, the armed wing of the Junta raided houses in Nat Myaung Village, Kale Township, Sagaing Region then arrested and killed Htay Win who was trapped in his house. The body of Htay Win discovered by locals was found with a knife wound and his hands tied behind his back.

On April 13, a fight broke out between the armed wing of the junta and the coalition of local defence forces in Pyi Taw Thar Village, Kale Township, Sagaing Region. During the battle, Nu Cing San Nuam, who was hiding in her house, got shot in her arm and legs and succumbed to the wounds due to blood loss.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On April 12, Ya Tu (aka) Sat Kyar Min, a member of the 1st Battalion of PDF Kalay was arrested by the junta soldiers while carrying out his reconnaissance duties. He was killed by immolation afterwards.

In the morning of April 16, Kyaw Min Htay, a native of Tharlar Wati Ward, Monywa Township, Sagaing Region, was arrested by the armed wing of the Junta and then was interrogated at a police station. Although he was let go after taking a mugshot, he was shot dead on his way home.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On April 14, at around 6 PM, Bol Gyi (aka Nay Min Kha), a member of the Black Dragon Special Task Force, was detained by the armed wing of the junta at his house in Myawaddy Ward, Monywa Township, Sagaing Region. He was tortured in an interrogation center and subsequently died on April 15 at around 4 PM.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: In the afternoon of April 9, Tin Tin Mya (aka) Soe Soe was taken hostage by the armed wing of the junta in her house at Mahar Nwesin Ward, Mahaaungmyay Township, Mandalay Region after they cannot locate her husband, the Vice Chairman of National League for Democracy (NLD) for Mandalay District; Ko Ko Lay, at home. While she was being captured, the soldiers skewered her hands and thighs with knife. On April 18, the body of Tin Tin Mya (aka) Soe Soe was found disposed of on the side of a road.

The victims are Htay Hla, Zaw, Win, Khin Htay, and Ohn Shwe.

In the morning and evening of April 20, the armed wing of the junta burned down the Nyaung Hla Village, Tabayin Township, Sagaing Region. They also captured a local villager Nay Myo Oo, then tortured and killed him with his hands tied behind his back. Nay Myo Oo was coming back to the village after sending away his family to take refuge in another village when he encountered the scouts and subsequently got arrested.
On April 19, the armed wing of the Junta raided the Muu Kha Twin Village in Tabayin Township, Sagaing Region, and shot Nu Sein and an old man to death.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On April 19, the armed wing of the Junta raided the Muu Kha Twin Village in Tabayin Township, Sagaing Region, and shot Nu Sein and an old man to death.

On April 19, six villagers living in Pae Yin Taung Village in Shan State’s Ywangan Township were killed by the armed wing of the junta for allegedly being personnel of a PDF group. Their bodies had been burned using car tires found at the plot of land which was located 100 yards to the east of the monastery at the center of the village. The six villagers were later identified as Tin Phay, Hla Soe, Tun Oo, Thet Aung, Myo Htwe and Win Naing. They had been arrested on April 16 while feeding their animals in the village. They attempted to evade the junta forces, as a ground offensive had been initiated in the village. After their deaths, three more villagers identified as Ba Htoo, Phoe Pyaung and Hla Shwin were arrested and detained for two days at the village monastery and on April 22, they were killed as well.

In the morning of April 23, the armed wing of the junta and Pyu Saw Htee Pro-junta Militia from Kin Poon Taw Village raided Inn Ma Village in Chaung-U Township, Sagaing Region and fired heavy artillery shells. A local villager named Win Myint was shot dead.

On January 4, a coalition of village administrators from Zee Taw Village, along with soldiers had been searching for NLD supporter Aung Kyin. He had been seeking refuge between Zee Taw and Kan Swe Village in Yesagyo Township, Magway Region and disappeared on the day he was being searched for. His corpse was discovered four days later.

According to Chin National Organization (CNO), Pu Ngun Hrin Hmung, from Chaung Gwa Village, Kale Township, Sagaing Region, was taken by the armed wing of the Junta and brought to O Myay Htoo Village where he was burned to death. When he was taken, on December 6, he was working in the bean fields of the Taung Hpa area.

In the early morning of April 23, junta soldiers raided Ywar Thar Village in Sagaing Region’s Khin-U Township by pretending to be members of the People’s defence forces (PDF). They killed Aung Naing Soe by shooting him in the back while he was on his way home. Additionally, Nyein Kyaw, who was arrested as a hostage, was killed after being tortured.

These shootings followed the death of a Pyu Saw Htee member living in that village who was killed the same day, in the morning.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On May 6, at around 4 AM, the armed wing of the junta came into Kan Thit Village, Budalin Township, Sagaing Region, and burned it down. An old woman was burned to death.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: စောဖားတရုတ်
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On May 5, at around 10 AM, the armed wing of the junta and their allies (BGF-1014) killed a local named Saw Phar Tayote (in Kyae Pha Lae) between Htee Kyu and Mae Tha Na Villages, Hpa-An Township, Kayin State. He was driving a motorbike to bring food for the cows and did not stop, and was shot in the back. The bullet perforated his bladder and killed him.

On May 4, at around 10 AM, the body of Kyi Win from Nyaung Pin Village, Myinmu Township, Sagaing Region, was found with a cut in the neck from a blade near Ba Dat Htine Village in Myinmu Township. He had previously been taken away by the armed wing of the junta when they burned down Ma Lae Thar Village in Myinmu Township, along with six other locals.

On April 30, a battle broke out between the armed wing of the junta and the people's defence force near Pyin Lay Pin Village, Inn Village Tract, Katha Township, Sagaing Region. The junta forces then arrested and immolated 4 villagers from Pyin Lay Pin, at Lwin Yar Field, near the village. Their names are Myo Thant,  Myint Tin, Soe Moe Aung and Win Myint. From April 27 to April 30, at least 30 civilians were arrested by the armed wing of the Junta to be used as human shields in Inn Village Tract.
