cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ငြိမ်းထက်အောင်
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On May 6, Junta soldiers opened fire near Pyin Chaung Village on two young men, who were going to Yangon from Kyunn Gyi Village, Pauk Township, Magway Region. One of them, Nyein Htet Aung was killed, and the other one was arrested.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: မြင့်သိန်း
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On May 6, junta soldiers and Pyu Saw Htee militia raided Zee Kone Kyunn Village, Yesagyo Township, Magway Region, and shot Myint Thein to death.

On May 6, the Junta soldiers raided Kan Thit (East) Village, Budalin Township, Sagaing Region, and burned down the village. The raid caused the death of Khin Myaing who was unable to run away from the fire.

Due to the Light Infantry Battalion 408 firing with heavy weaponry onto Ta Dwee Kho Village, Hpapun Township, Kayin State, Naw Sal Ei and Naw Thadar were injured by bomb shrapnels, respectively in the chest and in the stomach. The injuries of Naw Thadar were too serious and she died on May 8.
On May 2, the armed wing of the Junta raided Inn Pat Village in Khin-U Township and set fire to the village. During the raid, Naing Oo was burnt alive.

On the morning of February 25, the armed wing of the Junta raided and set fire to Hna Ma Sar Yit village, in Sagaing Region’s Shwebo Township. Khin Than died in the fire while she was hiding in the bathroom, as she was not able to run away. Ba Thein and Soe Lwin Oo were also unable to flee and burned to death. In addition, Yin Sann Aye and Thein were shot to death while running away with other villagers.

On May 11 at around  9 pm, Myo Myat Moe was shot to death by a policeman in  Zayat Gyi Police Precinct, Htantabin Township, Bago Region. He was killed in his home, located in an alley west of the police station for allegedly pointing a flashlight at said station.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: အောင်ထွန်း
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On May 11, the armed wing of the Junta raided Na Bu Taw Village in Sagaing Region’s Yinmarbin Township and shot a local villager called Aung Tun to death.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ဇော်ဝင်းဆန်း
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On May 11, the armed wing of the Junta raided Myoe Paw Village in Sagaing Region’s Budalin Township and shot a local villager called Zaw Win Hsann to death while he was running away.
Zayar Min, the owner of a timber factory, was arrested on May 10 following a shot being fired at an air force major in Shwedaung Township, Bago Region. He was then killed on May 12.

On April 30 at around 9:30 am, Mai Arr Ti, a village administrator of Pan Khar Lay Village in Shan State’s Lashio Township, was shot by the soldiers at a Mal Han Checkpoint as he drove through a checkpoint without stopping while returning home from Lashio. He died on the same day after being brought to Lashio Hospital.
On May 15 at around 7 am, the armed wing of the Junta raided the Hnaw Yoe Village in Sagaing Region’s Yinmarbin Township and shot a local villager called Aung Zaw Thein to death.
On May 14, the armed wing of the Junta raided Hmet Hti Village in Sagaing Region’s Wetlet Township and arrested and killed a local villager called Kyaw Hsann Naing.
On May 14, the armed wing of the Junta arrested and burned alive Kyaw Khaing from Bin Tae Kone Village in Sagaing Region’s Wetlet Township. He was killed near Sar Taung Gyi Village.

On May 14, the armed wing of the Junta raided Myoe Thit Village in Khin-U Township, Sagaing Region, and shot a local villager called Myint Soe to death at Lat Wae Kone, east of the village, while he was running away.

Wat Gyi, his wife Khin Htwe, and their son Ye Myint lived in Padauk Kan Village in Myaing Township, Magway Region. On May 13, they were killed when their home exploded due to the armed wing of the junta firing artillery shells before raiding their village.

Wat Gyi, his wife Khin Htwe, and their son Ye Myint lived in Padauk Kan Village in Myaing Township, Magway Region. On May 13, they were killed when their home exploded due to the armed wing of the junta firing artillery shells before raiding their village.

Wat Gyi, his wife Khin Htwe, and their son Ye Myint lived in Padauk Kan Village in Myaing Township, Magway Region. On May 13, they were killed when their home exploded due to the armed wing of the junta firing artillery shells before raiding their village.

Hlyan Khaw Shan from Tar Han Ward, Kale Township was feeling unwell on the evening of April 9. He was driving to the clinic when he went missing. On April 10, Kale  Military Hospital contacted his family and asked them to come to retrieve his body, which is how they found out he had died. He had been pulled over by policemen and soldiers, who were suspicious of him and died during interrogation. His family members testified to finding gunshot wounds on his leg as well as signs of physical torture all over his face and body.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ဇော်မင်းထွန်း (ခ) မင်းမင်း
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: Zaw Min Tun (aka) Min Min from Hinthar Kan Village, Paungde Township, Bago Region was arrested by the police while he was at his wife's Paan shop in Paungde on May 18 at around 1 PM after mines exploded on a police patrol on May 15 on Tha Phan Kone-Tar Pon Road which is two furlong away from Paan shop. On May 19, his family was brought to see his body. However, it is yet to be returned to them.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: မျိုးသီဟထွန်း (ခ) သီဟ
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: Myo Thiha Tun (aka) Thiha, a leader of the 11th segment of Bago PDF, was arrested on January 19 at the Thanatpin Checkpoint while he was on his way to Thanatpin from Bago alongside Htut Htut Win and Kyaw Swar Moe. He was then interrogated and forced to confess his connexion to the explosion that took place in January at the Road Transport Administration Department on Bago Bypass Road. He died on January 26 at 1:50 am.  Htut Htut Win and Kyaw Swar Moe were both sentenced to 19 years of imprisonment under Counter-Terrorism Law by the Taungoo Township Court.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ကျော်ညီဇင်
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On May 20, Kyaw Nyi Zin, 3rd year MB Student at the University of Medicine of Mandalay, was shot to death in the head by the junta while in a car on Mandalay-Monywa Road. He was involved in the Civil Disobedience Movement (CDM) and did not attend University anymore.

On May 19, five IDPs were shot to death by a military convoy firing artillery where they were taking refuge in Tar Tai Village. They are Win Ko, Kyaw Naing, Naing Linn Maung, Pyay and Tin Linn from Pauk Tar Village, from Sagaing Region’s Ye-U Township.

On the afternoon of May 20, the armed wing of the Junta raided In-Taing Lay Village in Khun-U Township, Sagaing Region by firing artillery shells. They then set fire to the village. cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: Pau Za Muang and Pau Suan Thang, living in Saii Zang Village in Chin State’s Tedim Township, were killed. On May 21, they were arrested at Sa Kaw Lan Ward in Tedim Town when they ran into soldiers on their way home from hunting in the jungle. They were killed for allegedly being part of the Chinland Defence Force (CDF) as they carried Tumee rifle when they returned.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldHfL2UA8oU0Imne: Hang Sian Awn (aka) Hein Htike Zaw
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On May 25, Hang Sian Awn (aka) Hein Htike Zaw was arrested and then shot to death by the armed wing of the junta in Pyay Village, Mindat Township, Chin State.  He was a boxer and represented Chin State.

On May 25, Chit Thein Zaw (aka) Phar Gyi and Kyaw Nyein from Ywar Thar Village, Salingyi Township, Sagaing Region were arrested and taken hostage by the junta's forces. Their hands were restrained behind their backs, and they were killed. Chit Thein Zaw had sustained injuries consistent with torture, along with three gunshot wounds: two on his forehead and one in his chest. He had been shot to death near a betel farm, located between Kan Kone and Done Taw Villages. Half of Kyaw Nyein's face had been deformed due to extreme torture, and he was discovered with a bullet wound on his head. He was killed at the Kunn Chan Cemetery. Both of them had been employees at Myanmar Yangtse Copper Co. Ltd. Kyaw Nyein worked in the Processing Department while Chit Thein Zaw worked as a Drill Operator in the Mining Department.

Thaw Ma Lawka, abbot of the Śāsana Zawti Pala Monastery, and farmers Zaw Wai and Nwe, who were husband and wife, were shot to death during the raid.

On May 28, at around 8 PM, heavy weaponry fired by the armed wing of the junta in Tar Han Ward, Kale Township, Sagaing Region, caused the death of 2 internally displaced persons (IDP) and a woman. All three died of the wounds caused by artillery shells. The two IDP; Ni Ni Aye and her son Bhone Myat Oo, were running away from Mingin to Kale Town. A woman, Vanlalawmpuii died on May 29, at 1 AM.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: Yan Naing Linn, an internally displaced person living in Ban Bwe Taw Pyin Village, Yinmarbin Township, Sagaing Region, was arrested by the junta on May 24. Two days later, his body was discovered in Thanatkha Yard.

6 locals from Kyauk Khwat, Baunt Bin, Baw Tone and Than Chaung Villages in Myaing Township, Magway Region were taken as human shields around May 23. 3 days later their bodies were discovered; each of them had 2 gunshot wounds in the head. One of them is Kyaw Ye from Kyauk Khwat Village.

Soe Thant and Nyi Nyi Win from Pint Thar Village in Kanbalu Township, Sagaing Region were arrested and killed by the armed wing of the Junta on May 29 at around 6 PM. When a clash broke out between the armed wing of the junta and the PDFs, Soe Thant and Nyi Nyi Win hid in a monastery. As there were no mosquito nets for them, they went home to get some and they encountered junta forces at the village entrance that were coming as reinforcement and who captured and killed them.

In the early morning of May 31, junta soldiers raided Kan Gyi (West) Village in Kanbalu Township, Sagaing Region. They arrested and killed 5 villagers: Maung Soe, Kyaw Myo Thu, Taw Shaung, Tun and Win Thura, who were guarding the village.

Khin Nyo, who is a secretary of the Women Working Committee for National League for Democracy in Tike Kone Ward in Nyaung-U Township, Mandalay Region, died in prison on June 28 at around 5:30 am due to deteriorating health conditions following her arrest on May 30.

On May 27, at around 2:30 PM, the armed wing of the junta opened fire on youth playing football inside a train station compound in Loikaw Township, Kayah State as they started fighting. A young man named Ah Ngal Du who was herding cows nearby got shot and died. Ah Ngal Du lived in the Kyi Tar Yar Ward near the train station and his father is a carriage driver.

On May 29, at around 3 PM, the armed wing of the junta, stationed in Kha Lae-Tagon Daing Area Police Station, Kyainseikgyi Township, Kayin State, opened fire on Nan Thaing Htun Village using heavy weaponry. As a result, Zin Oo was killed while cooking in her house, and her daughter got wounded on the cheek by the artillery fire.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldHfL2UA8oU0Imne: Saw Tha Phwe (aka) Bin Lar Din
cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: စောသဖွီး (ခ) ဘင်လာဒင်
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On May 28, at around 11 PM, NLD member Saw Tha Phwe (aka) Bin Lar Din, who lived in Hpa Do Town, Kyauktaga Township, Bago Region, was apprehended by the armed wing of the Junta. His hands and legs were tied and restrained, along with being gagged before being dragged around with a car. 2 days later, his family was informed of his passing. He had been on the run for a long time and got captured when he went home to see his wife who had severe health issues.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ဘုန်းကျော် (ခ) သက်လွင်ဦး
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On May 20, the armed wing of the Junta raided Gae Thar Hmway Village located in Sagaing Region’s Ayadaw Township, and arrested CDM teacher Bhone Kyaw (aka) Thet Lwin Oo for informing an informant of the Junta. Bhone Kyaw (aka) Thet Lwin Oo was killed on May 25, and on May 29 his body was found with signs of injuries consistent with torture.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ‌အောင်ကိုလင်း (ခ) ငဘန်
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On May 31, the Ka-Pa-Sa [Defence Industry – DI] (25) raided the Semee Village in Saw Township of Magway Region and arrested 3 youths, a woman and 1 passerby visitor. The woman was kept under house arrest at Laung Shay Town, and the other four males were taken to DI (25) base where they were tortured. This resulted in the death of the passerby visitor Aung Ko Linn (aka) Nga Ban, who was immediately buried afterwards. Aung Ko Linn (aka) Nga Ban was a CDM medic and served at the Saw Public Hospital as the 2nd ranked supervisor.

The armed wing of the junta stationed near Koe Htaung Bolt Village (in Sagaing Region’s Kanbalu Township) opened fire with heavy weaponry on the night of June 1. One of the artillery shells from the attack landed on a house and killed a family of 3: Zin Bhone, his mother Lae Lae Soe, and his grandfather Soe Kyaw.

In the morning of June 1, Kee Tang from Kanpetlet Town of Chin State was arrested by the armed wing of the junta for supposedly having photos of the comrades from CDF on his phone. He was taken into the yard of the Kanpetlet General Administration Office and was shot dead. His body was not returned to his family. Kee Tang was arrested at a Kanpetlet Checkpoint while he was on his way home on a car from Saw Township after buying a pig for a traditional Chin ceremony for his parent-in-law.

The armed wing of the junta raided and immolated Kyauk Taing Village in Wetlet Township of Sagaing Region on June 2.  This resulted in the deaths of Phoe Khae who suffered from a stroke, and Aye Nu died in the fire. Additionally, a disfigured body of a man, with injuries such as a swollen, purple head, was discovered. Presently, he has not been identified by locals.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: Four men, living in  Tazal Chaung Village of Sagaing Region’s Kani Township, who were refuging in the forest due to the ongoing conflict, were taken away by the soldiers on May 31 to be used as human shields. They were later killed on June 2 on one of the hills near the village. Their names were: Khin Maung Tint, Nga Zaw, Nga Pu and Eh Phyo.

On May 31, during a clash between the local PDFs and the armed wing of the junta in Oo Yin Thar Village, Wetlet Township of Sagaing Region, an artillery shell fired by the armed wing of the Junta exploded and injured a disabled woman - according to locals. Her name is Mone, and she died the next day from the wounds.

Nyan Win, a third-year student from Hpa-An University majoring in Mathematics, who was involved in the Civil Disobedience Movement (CDM), was shot, arrested, and tortured to death by the armed wing of the junta on June 4.

On June 1, members Hein Zayar Phyo and Hein Zayar Oo of the 2nd Unit of People's Defence Force (PDF) Battalion-1 of Kyaukpadaung Township in Mandalay Region, were arrested. On June 3, they were transferred  from Letpan Pyar Police Station to Division 99. On the early morning of June 4, they were tortured and killed during interrogation. Hein Zayar Phyo was shot and died from blood loss, Hein Zayar Oo was shot in the head at close range. At 3pm the same day, their bodies were cremated without informing the family members. They were living in Bo Tae Village in Kyaukpadaung Township and were distance education students from Myingyan University.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ချစ်ကိုကို
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: The armed wing of the junta stationed in Yinmarbin Town of Sagaing Region opened fire with heavy weaponry on June 5, at around 7 PM, resulting in the death of Chit Ko Ko living in Ward (A) of Yinmarbin Town. Chit Ko Ko was eating at his home when the attack occurred.

The armed wing of the junta raided Thar Ga Ya Village in Khin-U Township (Sagaing Region) on the evening of June 3 and burned down the houses the following morning. There was one recorded death of a civilian: Shi, who was unable to escape in time due to ill health and was burned alive.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: အောင်ကိုဝင်း
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: Aung Ko Win, an NLD party member from Htone Yay Pauk Village in Kachin State's Mogaung Township was shot dead by Pin Baw Village's Pyu Saw Htee militiamen, led by Kyaw Myint. The killing took place in his farm hut on June 5, at around 8:30 PM.

Wai Linn from Tha Yet Pin Village in Kani Township (Sagaing Region) was arrested, tortured, and shot dead by the armed wing of the junta. He was an internally displaced person who, on June 3, ran into the junta's army while trying to briefly go back home.

Chit Lwin, a palm tree climber from Daung Chan Village in Kani Township (Sagaing Region), was arrested by the armed wing of the junta on June 5, at 4 PM while climbing a palm tree. He was questioned and tortured at a farm, on the way from Nat Myauk Village to Nat Taung Village, and later immolated. In the evening of June 6, Chit Lwin's body was buried by his family.

On May 18, Zaw Linn, who lived in Kin Taung Village in Kani Township (Sagaing Region), was arrested and killed by the armed wing of the Junta. His body was found with knife injuries on his neck, chest and stomach, as well as bruises on his face, back, leg and head. His hands were tied behind his back.

In the evening of May 25, Aung Than Maw, who lives in Upper Kin Village in Kani Township (Sagaing Region), was arrested and killed by the armed wing of the Junta. They cut three of his fingers and toes on each side and cuffed his hands and neck.

The armed wing of the junta raided Kan Phyar Village in Myinmu Township (Sagaing Region) during the afternoon, on June 6. The soldiers came into Myat Saw Nyi Naung pagoda compound, where displaced civilians were taking refuge. They searched the motorbikes that were parked in the pagoda compound and said they found a gun hidden under one of the seats. They asked whose bike that was but the villagers said they didn’t know. As a result, the soldiers set all the bikes on fire. They also picked out around 30 men out of the 100 displaced people, and gave them 10 seconds to start running. When they did, around 20 soldiers began shooting at them from behind; resulting in the death of 6 men. Another three were shot to death in front of other villagers after they were told to place their hands on their heads. Two other villagers were found dead inside the burnt down Buddhist monastery. The ages of those who were executed ranged from 17 to over 60 years old and they are Hla Soe, Myint Oo, CDM teacher Nay Zar Aung, Yupa, Aung Min Naing, Paing Paing, Mae Gyi, Thura, Tin Htwe, San and an unidentified person. Among them, Paing Paing suffered from polio and a mental illness. Soldiers ganged up on him, kicked and stepped on him, resulting in him kicking them back. The soldiers then threw him into the fire, according to a displaced person.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ခင်မောင်ချင်း
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: The armed wing of the Junta was stationed in Nyaung Lal Village in Gangaw Township (Magway Region) for three days starting June 2. During that time, seven local villagers were killed. Two villagers from Nyaung Lal Village named Khin Maung Chin and Naing, who suffered from a mental illness, were burnt alive to death. The bodies of the five other villagers are yet to be identified by locals. it is unknown on which date they were killed.

The armed wing of the Junta was stationed in Nyaung Lal Village in Gangaw Township (Magway Region) for three days starting June 2. During that time, seven local villagers were killed. cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ဇေယျာခိုင်
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On June 8, the armed wing of the Junta raided Bo Tae Village in Sagaing Region’s Wetlet Township and burned Zayar Khaing to death. He had been hiding during the raid but attempted to go back home when the gunfire stopped, as he was hungry. That is when all contact with him was lost.
On June 9, the armed wing of the Junta and Pyu Saw Htee militiamen raided Thae Taw Village in Yesagyo Township (Magway Region) and burned Aye to death.

Kan Myint, who is a member of a defence force in Chaung-U Township (Sagaing Region), was captured by the armed wing of the Junta while attempting to fend off a raid on his home village of Ta Pei Inn on June 5. He got shot while he was waiting to attack the military with explosives. He was tied up and beaten before being burnt alive to death.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: သန်းသန်းဦး
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On June 8 at around 9 am, Than Than Oo, living in Taw Pu Village in Monywa Township (Sagaing Region), was shot to death on her way home by four Pyu Saw Htee militiamen from the same village. She was killed upon reaching the Kokeko Trees path in Taung Pon Village after selling flowers in Monywa Town.

In the morning of June 9, the armed wing of the Junta raided Ta Ohn Village in Shwebo Township (Sagaing Region) and shot five villagers to death. One of them, named Aung Hsann, was shot dead as soldiers found him while he was trying to hide.

In the morning of June 8, the 363rd Light Infantry Battalion entered Lar Poe Village in Gangaw Township (Magway Region) and killed two villagers; Chit Shine and Wai Linn Oo (aka) Hsan Shay, accusing them of being PDF members. Their bodies were then disposed of at a rest house at the entrance of the village and burned down.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ဝေလင်းဦး (ခ) ဆံရှည်

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ငိုင်ရှမ်းနဲမ်
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On June 10, at 7 PM, a Chin woman named Ngai Sian Nem was shot dead by the armed wing of the junta near the army base in Tamu Town, while she was going home from Kale Town (Sagaing Region).

On June 10, at around 9 PM, the 102nd Infantry Battalion, based in Ngwe Taung, used heavy weaponry on Saung Dular Village in Demoso Township (Kayah State). The attack caused the death of Ko Yii whose house got hit by an artillery shell. 3 other people got injured, including a 5-year-old child.

On June 11, at 6:20 AM, a clash broke out between the armed wing of the junta and the alliance of the people's defence forces near the Laung Daw Oo Pagoda and Hlay Bo Village in Katha Township (Sagaing Region). During the battle, the junta forces fired heavy weaponry on 6 Internally displaced people when soldiers saw them looking at the clash. The junta’s shooting caused the death of four of them, while the other two are heavily injured. The deceased are called Ou Ti Bwar, Maung Zaw, Zin Maung Maung and Aung Zaw Naing.

On June 12, at around 3 PM, Pann Ei Phyu from Late Kyal Pyaung Village in Tanintharyi Region was shot dead by a military convoy going from Kyaukme Taung Village to Dawei Town. The junta soldiers from the convoy were shooting at random; she got hit while trying to flee her house, that was being shot at.

In the night of June 9, the Sittaung Rescue Team vehicle was attacked by the armed wing of the junta, on the way back from the hospital after transporting a patient. From their secret watching post in front of Lat Pan Pin Cementary, in Ingabo Village (Kyaikto Township, Mon State), the Junta attacked, using all kinds of light and heavy weaponry. As a result, Pyae Phyo Aung was shot in the bladder and died while being transported to Kyaikto Township Hospital.

Nanda and Chan Ko, two members of Chaung-U Township’s People's Defence Force, were arrested and killed by the Pyu Saw Htee militiamen and the armed wing of the junta, stationed in Kan Gyi Kone Village (Chaung-U Township, Sagaing Region) in the morning of June 7. They were part of the production branch of Chaung-U PDF.

Nanda and Chan Ko, two members of Chaung-U Township’s People's Defence Force, were arrested and killed by the Pyu Saw Htee militiamen and the armed wing of the junta, stationed in Kan Gyi Kone Village (Chaung-U Township, Sagaing Region) in the morning of June 7. They were part of the production branch of Chaung-U PDF.

On June 10, Pyu Saw Htee militiamen and the junta’s Shwebo No 8 Training Corp raided Ta Ohn Village in Shwebo Township (Sagaing Region) and shot a local named Hnin Maung to death. 7 villagers were then taken as human shields; Kyaw Linn, Sein Mann, Maung Htoo, Win Swe, Thein Tan, Phoe Htoo and Ye Wai Linn. When they reached Boe Noe Dam to the east of Gyogyar Village on June 12, they were tied up and shot dead. Their bodies were disposed of on the dam.

In Yesagyo township, Magway, the junta captured 2 resistance fighters, a nurse, a headmaster and a pregnant teacher, before killing them. They were arrested together when the armed wing of the junta raided the base of North Yesagyo (N-YSO) in the Magway Region. The deceased were Senior Nurse Zar Li Naing, Head Master Win Kyaw, and 5-months-pregnant teacher, Khin Hnin Wai, who were CDM workers, as well as, and a member of the support team of North Yesagyo (N-YSO), Thae Ei Ei Win, and Htay Min Oo (aka) Wu Khone. In addition, their bodies were burned.

On June 11, the armed wing of the junta raided Kyoe Kan Village in Khin-U Township (Sagaing Region) and burned down houses. They then tortured and shot two people to death, including Chan Thar, in a village west of Kyoe Kan Village. Both were from Indaing Gyi Village, Khin-U Township, and were taken as human shields.

Aye May who had a stroke, was unable to run away and was left behind in her house when the armed wing of the junta came into Ah Shay Kan Phyu Village (Pakokku Township, Magway Region). She died when her house was set on fire.

Starting June 8, the armed wing of the junta has been attacking Pakokku Township (Magway Region) and in Taung Palu Village of the township, many locals, including Soe Han, got tortured. His injuries were too serious for him to be able to run away and when his son came to rescue him on June 11, he passed away within five minutes of being found.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: သက်ပိုင်ဦး
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On June 15, three Twae Ma Shaung  PDF members from Yinmarbin Township, Sagaing Region, were arrested and killed by the armed wing of the Junta because of an attack on the Junta’s column of vehicles with mines between Lat Taung Nge Village and Tha Yet Kan Village. These three PDF members were Thet Paing Oo, Hein Htet Soe and Min Bo Bo.

On the night of June 16, a  house in Gawt Inn Village, Launglon Township, Tanintharyi Region, was raided and shot at by the junta. They killed a local in that house named Amy Phyo Wai, who was shot in the head and died on the spot; her house was also burned down. Her brother was a CDM worker and she was shot dead as the junta did not find out his current location.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldHfL2UA8oU0Imne: Kyaw Mya Than (aka) Bo Thanmani (aka) Maung Maung
cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ကျော်မြသန်း (ခ) ဗိုလ်သံမဏိ (ခ) မောင်မောင်
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On June 9, at 6:30 PM, a fight broke out between the junta’s Light Infantry Division 33 and the Shwebo Defence Force (SBDF) near Chaung Mee Toe Village, Wetlet Township, Sagaing Region. It resulted in the arrest of SBDF leader Bo Thanmani (aka) Kyaw Mya Than (aka) Maung Maung who was later was shot and killed, through a shot to the head and one to the heart.
At Pin Si High School in Ponar Kar Village in Ye-U Township, Sagaing Region, 3 miles to the west of Mone Taing Pin Village, Aung Myo Htet was arrested, chopped into three pieces, and killed.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On May 10, the armed wing of the junta raided Mone Taing Pin Village in Ye-U Township, Sagaing Region, and arrested 28 locals. A military convoy carrying around 180 soldiers attacked Gangaw Township on June 12, but they left behind this ordnance.

The bodies of two National League for Democracy (NLD) members, Pann Myint and Ko Ko Maung, were found near Dani Chaw Village in Mon State’s Bilin Township on July 2. They were previously detained by the regime alongside lawmaker Kyaw Myo Min, who is also the chairman of the Bilin Township NLD. They were captured on June 22, near the village of Lel Ka Te, after running into 100 junta troops who were advancing from Mae Pali strategic hill in Bilin. Their hands were tied behind their backs and they were taken to Dawkangyi Village monastery, where they were beaten during interrogation. On June 30, they were killed.

On the morning of June 21, the armed wing of the junta raided Moe Gyo Pyin (North) Village, near Letpadaung Copper Mining Project in Salingyi Township, Sagaing Region. Their bodies were discovered on the morning of June 22 by some locals in the field near the village. Tin Soe's neck was severed and his body was sliced with blades all over like a fish. Pwa Gyi got both of his hands cut down from his wrists and was disemboweled and his guts were falling out.

They were then shot in the head, stomach, waist, and eyes at close range; killing them instantly. Both Thaung Win and Win Aye were involved in anti-coup movements, and had supported the youth protesters.

The junta forces took 2 people from Yazee Byar detainment; Zin Ko Oo and Chan Thar, as guides, when they launched an attack at Nyaung Yin Village, Pauk Township, Magway Region. Then they were shot dead on the road.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On June 23, at around 1 PM, the junta’s 404th Light-Infantry Battalion, and other forces under 8th Regional Military Command stationed in Bilin Township, Mon State, fired artillery weapons. One of the shells landed next to a house in Ah Su Chaung Village. Killing a school teacher called Naw Hsann Hsann Win (aka Naw Aye) and 1 year, and 2 months old son.

Beginning from the evening of June 25, a coalition of the armed wing of the Junta and Border Guard Force troops entered Htone Bo Lay Village, Weyaw Village Tract, Thaton Township, Mon State, and set it on fire. During the incident, Saw Sa Moo, a disabled person, was shot dead as he could not run away.

On June 22, Lu Min, a ninth-grade student who withdrew from school because he did not want to participate in the junta's education system was shot dead by a military junta column, in a field near Kan Thit Village, Khin-U Township, Sagaing Region. The killing occurred following a clash near Kan Thit Village, when a military column came to support junta troops, and then shot Lu Min on sight.

On June 23 at around 9 pm, a mother and daughter named Pauk and War Moe, living in Kyaung Ywar Ward in Chaung-U Town, Sagaing Region, were killed on the spot when a junta artillery shell landed on their house. The armed wing of the junta stationed at Chang-U Town fired seven artillery shells into Kyaung Ywar Ward and Anout Ma Oak Ward, located to the south of Khin-U Town that night.

Myint Wai from Lone Gyi Village and a PDF member called Myo Swe were killed by the armed wing of the junta in Myaing Township, Magway Region. On June 16, Myint Wai was shot dead after trying to escape when local villagers were told to sit down by junta troops. On the morning of June 16, a clash occurred when a military column arrived at Pyin Thar Village before advancing to Lone Gyi Village. During the clash, a PDF member called Myo Swe was detained by the junta. His body was later found burned, but it is unknown which date he was killed.

On June 25, the armed wing of the Junta raided and set fire to Phaung Ka Dar Village, Salingyi Township, Sagaing Region. They captured a villager named Sai Myat Soe and killed him at the entrance of the village after torturing him.

On June 24, Maung Toe, living in Aung Thitsar Ward, Kale Township, Sagaing Region, was arrested at home as a hostage when the junta could not find his son. Then on June 27, the junta informed the family of Maung Toe to retrieve his dead body.

Nine Khaw Gay, living in Madat Village in Mindat Township, Chin State, was killed by the Junta artillery shell. On June 29, the Infantry Battalion (IB) 274, located in Mindat Town, Chin State, fired artillery shells at Madat Village and Kyar Eain Nue Village. The artillery shell landed in Madat Village and killed Naing Khaw Gay.

Local villagers fled when a clash occurred between the Karen National Liberation Army (KNLA) and the armed wing of the Junta on June 25 at 7 am between Nga Byat Inn Village and Inn Nat Village in Kyaukkyi Township, Bago Region. On June 26, three villagers attempting to re-enter Inn Nat Village ran away when they heard gunshots, before which, they had let the buffaloes tied up the day before free. Two of the three villagers disappeared while running away. On June 29, the body of one of the missing villagers, Saw Moo Thar, was found by villagers in search for them near the banana farm, located east of Inn Nat Monastery. He was killed by the armed wing of the Junta. Three mines were planted under the body. The other missing villager has not been found.

In the afternoon on June 29, nine members of the GZ Special Task Force (Wetlet) were arrested and killed near Kun Seik Village in Shwebo Township, Sagaing Region by the armed wing of the Junta. They ran into the armed wing of the junta while traveling from Wetlet township to Ayadaw township to attend medical training, and were killed.

They ran into the armed wing of the junta while traveling from Wetlet township to Ayadaw township to attend medical training, and were killed.

On June 15, Kyaw Lwin, owner of a livestock farm located next to Nan Tha Lae Bridge in Min Thar Village in Tamu Township, Sagaing Region, was beaten to death by the armed wing of the Junta and Pyu Saw Htee militiamen at Min Thar Cemetery. After, they burned his body. On June 14, soldiers and Pyu Saw Htee militiamen arrived at his farm and searched his hut due to allegations against him for keeping weapons there. They confiscated two phones and over 30 million Kyat from Kyaw Lwin, and when he went to Min Thar Police Station on June 15 to try to get his belongings back, he was kicked out. When he returned, he was followed by the armed wing of the Junta and Pyu Saw Htee militiamen and was arrested and taken to the Min Thar Cemetary and then killed.

On June 25, the armed wing of the Junta raided and set fire to Phaung Ka Dar Village, Salingyi Township, Sagaing Region. They captured a villager named Win Aung and killed him at the entrance of the village after torturing him.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ဗန်လျန်ထန်
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On July 2, Vum Lian Thang, a paraplegic man from Hlanzawl Village, Falam Township, Chin State, was dragged by the armed wing of the Junta with his hands tied behind his back and killed.

On June 30, Tial Kap, a disabled from Verlone Village, Falam Township, Chin State, was shot dead by the armed wing of the Junta who were advancing from Kale Town in Sagaing Region to Falam Town in Chin State. Her body was found on July 3, with a gunshot wound in her head according to locals.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: နေလင်းထွန်း
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On July 2 at 4:55 pm, the junta’s coalition between the Light Infantry Battalion 439 and 351, and Infantry Battalion 60, raided Law Mu Pal Village in Bago Region’s Kyaukkyi Township and shot four local villagers to death. Of these, only Nay Linn Tun and Saw Mar Nay Htoo have been identified. Saw Mar Nay Noo was working in his motorcycle repair shop when he was killed.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: မောင်မောင်
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On  June 30 at around 7:30 pm, Maung Maung and Saw Khant Aye, living in Thit Wah Village and Kaw Ta Yar Village in Hpa-An Township, Kayin State, stepped on a landmine planted by the armed wing of the Junta and the Border Guard Force (BGF) and died instantly. They left on motorbike to repair other people’s phones in Naw Pha Doe Village, Kyauk Ta Lone village tract. When returning, they were killed by a landmine located along the War Boe forest west of the Than Lwin River in Hpa-An Town.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: စောခန့်အေး
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On  June 30 at around 7:30 pm, Maung Maung and Saw Khant Aye, living in Thit Wah Village and Kaw Ta Yar Village in Hpa-An Township, Kayin State, stepped on a landmine planted by the armed wing of the Junta and the Border Guard Force (BGF) and died instantly. They left on motorbike to repair other people’s phones in Naw Pha Doe Village, Kyauk Ta Lone village tract. When returning, they were killed by a landmine located along the War Boe forest west of the Than Lwin River in Hpa-An Town.

On June 25, a coalition of the armed wing of the Junta and Border Guard Force troops entered Htone Bo Lay Village in Weyaw Village Tract, Thaton Township, Mon State, and set it on fire. During the incident, Saw Maung Lu Pyo and a monk named Tee Htoe Pa Whie were killed and their bodies were burned.

On June 25, a coalition of the armed wing of the Junta and Border Guard Force troops entered Htone Bo Lay Village in Weyaw Village Tract, Thaton Township, Mon State, and set it on fire. During the incident, Saw Maung Lu Pyo and a monk named Tee Htoe Pa Whie were killed and their bodies were burned.

On July 6, the body of lawmaker and chairman of Bilin Township NLD, Kyaw Myo Min, was found in a ditch located 300 feet from where two NLD members, Pann Myint, and Ko Ko Maung, were buried. The bodies of Pann Myint and Ko Ko Maung were found near Dani Chaw Village in Mon State’s Bilin Township on July 2. Kyaw Myo Min had represented Bilin township as the elected state MP. Kyaw Myo Min was shot in the head and his hands were cuffed behind his back. Kyaw Myo Min, Pann Myint, and Ko Ko Maung were captured near Lel Ka Te village on June 22, after running into 100 junta troops who were advancing from Mae Pali strategic hill in Bilin Township, Mon State. Their hands were tied behind their back and they were taken to Dawkangyi Village monastery, where they were beaten during interrogation. On June 30, they were killed.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: မင်းမင်းစိုး
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On July 3, during a clash with the People’s Defence Forces (PDF) in East Wetlet Township, Sagaing Region, the armed wing of the junta killed two villagers who were close by. These two villagers were Min Min Soe from Paline Kan Village and Maung Soe from Min Village.

On July 3, during a clash with the People’s Defence Forces (PDF) in East Wetlet Township, Sagaing Region, the armed wing of the junta killed two villagers who were close by. These two villagers were Min Min Soe from Paline Kan Village and Maung Soe from Min Village.

A local villager named Mone Phay was tortured to death after being captured when the military column raided Yae Shin Village in Sagaing Region’s Kale Township on July 4. When the military column left the village on July 6, the body of Mone Pe was cremated.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: သိန်းထွန်းဦး
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On July 4, the armed wing of the Junta raided Yone Pin Kone Village in Wetlet Township, Sagaing Region. They shot and killed a local villager, Thein Tun Oo, and then burned his body. Thein Tun Oo had previously suffered from a mental illness.

On July 7, the armed wing of the Junta raided and set fire to Mwae Tone Village and Min Village in Pale Township, Sagaing Region. During the incident, Tin Phay from Mwae Tone Village and Kyaw Han from Min Village were burnt alive because they were unable to run away.

On July 7, the armed wing of the Junta raided and set fire to Mwae Tone Village and Min Village in Pale Township, Sagaing Region. During the incident, Tin Phay from Mwae Tone Village and Kyaw Han from Min Village were burnt alive because they were unable to run away.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldHfL2UA8oU0Imne: Saw Ler Ka Paw (aka) Phar Baw
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On July 4, Saw Ler Ka Paw (aka) Phar Baw, a local Kayin Social Worker in Kyaukkyi Township, Bago Region, was arrested by Junta. After, he was interrogated and beaten at Awng Laung Sein military base, and then taken to Kyun Pin Seik military base. He died when being severely beaten again in interrogation. In addition, 5 million Kyat that was allocated for buying basic necessities for IDPs, was confiscated from him.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ဝင်းနိုင်ထွန်း
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On July 4 at around 7 pm, the Junta soldiers raided Gway Gone Village in Magway Region’s Yesagyo Township and shot local villager Win Naing Tun to death.

On the evening of July 9, Moung Sung Kai, living in Chan Myae Aung Si Ward, Kale Township, Sagaing Region, was shot in his back by Junta soldiers near Seik Kan Thar Market while on a motorbike that has a side carriage; he was giving a ride for his friends. Although he was sent to the hospital, he died on July 10 at 3 am.

Hnin Wai and her husband fled from their village in Seikphyu Township, Magway Region, following a raid by the armed wing of the junta in Seikphyu Township. They returned to Pine Village on July 9, to feed their pigs, and they came across 5 junta soldiers at the village entrance, who then chased them. Hnin Wai was arrested, killed and potentially raped also.

On July 10, Ni Lone, living in Sai Naing Lay Village, Wetlet Township, Sagaing Region, died on the spot when the Infantry Battalion 42 fired heavy artillery at Sai Naing Lay Village. They attacked after a military vehicle had been hit by a mine near Sai Naing Lay Village.

On July 11, the armed wing of the junta raided Taung Ywar Thit Village in Pale Township, Sagaing Region. Junta troops killed Moe Yii, and she was alleged to have been raped. Aye Win, Moe Yii’s mother, Tin Maung, and Nyo Kyin were also shot dead. Tin Maung was pulled up by the neck with a rope, and shot in the chest after coming across military troops, the others were shot in the head.

On July 11, the armed wing of the junta raided Taung Ywar Thit Village in Pale Township, Sagaing Region. Junta troops killed Moe Yii, and she was alleged to have been raped. Aye Win, Moe Yii’s mother, Tin Maung, and Nyo Kyin were also shot dead. Tin Maung was pulled up by the neck with a rope, and shot in the chest after coming across military troops, the others were shot in the head.

On July 11, the armed wing of the junta raided Taung Ywar Thit Village in Pale Township, Sagaing Region. Junta troops killed Moe Yii, and she was alleged to have been raped. Aye Win, Moe Yii’s mother, Tin Maung, and Nyo Kyin were also shot dead. Tin Maung was pulled up by the neck with a rope, and shot in the chest after coming across military troops, the others were shot in the head.

On July 11, the armed wing of the junta raided Taung Ywar Thit Village in Pale Township, Sagaing Region. Junta troops killed Moe Yii, and she was alleged to have been raped. Aye Win, Moe Yii’s mother, Tin Maung, and Nyo Kyin were also shot dead. Tin Maung was pulled up by the neck with a rope, and shot in the chest after coming across military troops, the others were shot in the head.

On July 8, the armed wing of the Junta entered Thel Taw Village, Yesagyo Township, Magway Region, and arrested and killed a local villager named Thein Zaw, who suffers from a mental illness. After, they burned Thein Zaw's body, which was later found near Thel Taw Monastery.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ပိုင်ပိုင်
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On July 10 at around 3 am, Paing Paing, living in Myoe Thit Ward, Dawei Township, Tanintharyi Region, was killed after being shot in the neck and stomach by the armed wing of the Junta near DDPC Shopping Center. He was fired at because he did not stop his motorbike after Junta told him to, but instead drove away. His family knew of his death after being contacted to retrieve his body at the hospital the following day.

On July 11, Myint Aye, living in Inn Net Village, Kyaukkyi Township, Bago Region, was arrested and killed by the Junta. He had come back to his home to set the cows who had been left behind free. Inn Net Villagers ran away when Junta fired small and heavy weaponry at the village.

On July 14 at 2:20 pm, Saw Shee May was killed, and two of his children named Naw Htee Hser Khu and Saw Htee Phoe Klo got injured by Junta’s heavy artillery shell. The Light Infantry Battalion (LIB) 351, Infantry Battalion (IB) 60, and coalition force fired heavy artillery at Set Lal Village in Kyaukkyi Township, Bago Region, which is where the deceased lived.
On July 14 at 7 am, the armed wing of the Junta arrested and killed Saw Ler Bu, who was living in Thaung Pu Village, Kyaukkyi Township, Bago Region.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: အောင်ချမ်းမင်း
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On July 10, Aung Chan Min, living in Hlay Tan Kyun Gyi Village, Kyaukkyi Township, Bago Region, died while receiving medical treatment at Ka Nyin Kyoe Hospital. He was seriously injured after stepping on a landmine that had been planted by Junta in Kyun Gyi Port on July 9.

On July 8, Kyaw Myint, living in Tawkashat Village and who is a township executive member of the Nation League for Democracy of Kanbalu Township, Sagaing Region, was arrested and killed by Pyu Saw militiamen. They had accused him of acting as an informant during the arrests of three men, including the son of the Tawkashat Village Pyu Saw Htee leader, which was led by the local People’s Defence Force earlier in the month. Kyaw Myint’s body was not returned to the family but cremated by the orders of the Junta.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: မြတ်သန္တာ အောင်
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On July 17, the armed wing of the Junta fired artillery weapons at Sal Village, Myaung Township, Sagaing Region. An artillery shell landed on a teashop in the village, and Myat Thandar Aung died instantly.

On July 14, at 9 PM, Zaw Khaing, who is living in Myoma (13) Nan Phar Lone, Tamu Township, Sagaing Region, was killed by four Pyu Saw Htee militiamen inside his house. Afterwards, his body was disposed of beside a stream.
On July 13, the junta forces set Mee Mung Kone Village in Ye-U Township, Sagaing Region, on fire, and 87-year-old Than Hti died from this.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: စိုင်းဝဏ္ဏ
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On July 16, Sai Wunna from Karenni Democratic Front (KDF) died in interrogation. He was arrested in front of the 261 Artillery Battalion in Loikaw in May, after being questioned.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ပြည့်စုံဦး
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On July 18, Pyae Sone Oo, from Sein Thar Village, Ayadaw Township, Sagaing Region, was driving on a motorbike by Ayadaw-Wadawma Road and refused to stop when the armed wing of the Junta tried to pull him over near Kwae Chan Village. The junta troops fatally shot him, and his body was disposed of on the side of the road. Junta forces also confiscated his motorbike and phone. Pyae Sone Oo was returning to the village when he was shot in the chest and thigh.

At around 7 PM on July 18, Sai Thiha, living in Taung Hyoe Village, Tangyan Township, Shan State, was driving a car when it was shot at by the armed wing of the Junta. This resulted in the death of Sai Thiha's wife, Nang Seng Lu, and his 3-year-old son. Sai Thiha died whilst being treated for his wounds at Mongshu Hospital. The family was shot at while they were returning from Mongshu Town to Taung Hyoe Village.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: At around 7 PM on July 18, Sai Thiha, living in Taung Hyoe Village, Tangyan Township, Shan State, was driving a car when it was shot at by the armed wing of the Junta. The family was shot at while they were returning from Mongshu Town to Taung Hyoe Village.

At around 11 PM on July 18, the armed wing of the junta failed to pull over 3 youths on a motorbike by Shwe Lin Ban Bridge on Kyansittha Road, Hlaingtharya Township, Yangon Region. As a result, they were chased down by a car and shot at. Two out of three youths died, while one managed to escape. The deceased were Wai Yan and Toe Gyi. Wai Yan got shot in the head, and Toe Gyi got shot in the stomach but died whilst being treated in hospital.

At around 11 PM on July 18, the armed wing of the junta failed to pull over 3 youths on a motorbike by Shwe Lin Ban Bridge on Kyansittha Road, Hlaingtharya Township, Yangon Region. As a result, they were chased down by a car and shot at. Two out of three youths died, while one managed to escape. The deceased were Wai Yan and Toe Gyi. Wai Yan got shot in the head, and Toe Gyi got shot in the stomach but died whilst being treated in hospital.

At around 2 AM on July 19, No. 285 Battalion based in Palaw fired with heavy weaponry at Peinne Taung Village, Palaw Township, Tanintharyi Region. One of the artillery shells landed on a house and killed a local named Zin Wine.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ခင်မောင်ဆန်း
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: Three civilians and seven Local People Defence’s Force members were arrested and killed, as they were unable to escape when the armed wing of the Junta attacked. The Junta fired with air strikes and then raided and set fire to Kyi Su Village in Kanbalu Township, Sagaing Region on July 18, 2021. Furthermore, the bodies of the deceased were burned, except for the body of Moe Thin, who suffered from a mental illness. In addition, two Local People Defence’s Force members who were entering the village were fatally shot when they ran into the some members of the armed wing of the Junta who were left behind in Thar Wutthti Village in Khin-U Township.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: အောင်နိုင်ဝင်း
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: In the morning of July 20, the armed wing of the junta raided Shin Min Dway Village, Khin-U Township, Sagaing Region. Consequently, an NLD party member named Aung Naing Win was captured and fatally shot while trying to escape. His body was later discovered and burned inside one of the houses that had been set on fire.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldHfL2UA8oU0Imne: Aung Min Htwe (aka) Aung Myint Htwe
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: At around 9 AM on July 6, Khin Maung Than, a hundred-household administrator of No.22 Ward, Dagon Myothit (South) Township, Yangon Region, was waiting on top of the street for a civilian named Aung Min Htwe (aka) Aung Myint Htwe. However, when Aung Min Htwe arrived he was attacked by Khin Maung Than for no apparent reason; and he was sent to Sanpya hospital for treatment, but passed away at 11:45 AM. His medical report stated that he died from internal injuries.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: အမည်စုံစမ်းဆဲ
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On July 19, a local man from Tarlaw Gyi VIllage, Waingmaw Township, Kachin State, was going to the west of the village on a bike to make a payment in regards to building a house. While he was on his way, he refused to stop when Shanni Militia tried to pull him over. As a result, he got shot 5 times, and one of the bullet's hit him in the genital area. He was urgently transported from Tarlaw Gyi Hospital to a military hospital in Myitkyina Town, but unfortunately he bled to death. The militia also confiscated 5,600,000 Kyat and two phones from him, which the village elders tried to ask back, but only retrieved 600,000 Kyat and one phone.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldHfL2UA8oU0Imne: Phyo Zayar Thaw (aka) Maung Kyaw (aka) Yay Khe
cellValuesByColumnId.fld7KLBHB6DdATjnu: Dr Mya Thaw + Daw Khin  Win May
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: Phyo Zayar Thaw, (aka) Maung Kyaw (aka) Yay Khe, was a Hip-Hop artist from ACID Band. He was a founder and chairman of the "Generation Wave" - which represents the new generation. Phyo Zayar Thaw, who was arrested at a Yangon restaurant with friends on 12 March 2008 and on 20 November 2008, he was sentenced to five years imprisonment under the Unlawful Associations Act. He served his sentence at Kawthoung prison and was released on 17 May 2011. He was a member of the National League for Democracy. In the 2012 Myanmar by-elections, he contested the Poke Ba Thi Ri Township constituency for a seat in the House of Representatives, the country's lower house, in the 2015 Myanmar general election, he contested the Za Bu Thi Ri Township constituency and won a House of Representatives seat. From 2012 to 2021, he served as a representative of Pyithu Hluttaw. He was arrested on November 18 at Yadanar Hnin Si  Housing in Dagon Myothit (Seikkan) for opposing against Junta in Yangon during the 2021 Spring Revolution. On January 21, 2022, the military tribunal sentenced him to death under charges of the Counter-Terrorism Law Section 49 (a), 50 (i) and 50 (j). On July 23, 2022, the junta unjustly executed him in Insein Prison.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ကျော်မင်းယု (ခ) ဂျင်မီ
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: Kyaw Min Yu (aka) Jimmy was a Burmese writer, former political prisoner, political activist and a member of the 88 Generation Peace and Open Society. He rose to prominence during the 8888 Uprising, as a student activist. He spent 15 years, from 1988 to 1996, in prison for participating in the 8888 Uprising. He was released from prison on 13 January 2012, after spending another five years in prison, for protesting fuel price hikes with the 88 Generation Students Group in August 2007. He was arrested on October 23, 2021, in Pinlon Housing in Dagon Myothit (North) Township, for revolting against Junta in Yangon during the Spring Revolution 2021. On January 21, 2022, the military tribunal sentenced him to death with charges under Penal Code Section 505 (A), 124, Unlawful Associations Act Section 17 (a), Counter-Terrorism Law, The Arms Act and Explosive Substances Act. On July 23, 2022, the junta unjustly executed him in Insein Prison.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldHfL2UA8oU0Imne: Hla Myo Aung (aka) Ko Myo (aka) Wet Gyi
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: Hla Myo Aung, (aka) Ko Myo (aka) Wetgyi, was a local from Hlaingtharya Township, Yangon Region. He was accused of the murder of Win Than Dar Swe from Hlaingtharya Township, and was arrested on March 2021. He was charged under Penal Code Section 302 (1)(b)/34 and was sentenced to death by the military tribunal on April 12, 2021. On July 24, 2022, the junta unjustly executed him in Insein Prison.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: အောင်သူရဇော် (ခ) ကတုံး (ခ) သူရ
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: Aung Thura Zaw (aka) Gatone (aka) Thura, was a local from Hlaingtharya Township, Yangon Region. He was accused of the murder of Win Than Dar Swe from Hlaingtharya Township and was arrested on March 2021. He was charged under Penal Code Section 302 (1)(b)/34 and was sentenced to death by the military tribunal on April 12, 2021. On July 24, 2022, the junta unjustly executed him in Insein Prison. Aung Thura Zaw's pregnant wife faced difficulties as she would soon be giving birth, was struggling financially, and her long commute to visit her husband in Daik-U Prison, Bago Region, was becoming challenging.

On November 18, 2021, Pwar and Htet Oo from Nat Nan Village, Wundwin Township, Mandalay Region, were hanging out and eating with their friends at a friend’s house, when police forces from Wundwin Police Station and troops from Meiktila-based Division 99 came. The police and troops opened fire, and arrested and killed them. The raid and killing took place because an informant had tipped off the junta forces about the presence of the People's Defence Forces. Pwar was a trainee of the Wundwin Township Revolutionary Force training camp, while Htet Oo was a civilian.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: At around 8 AM on July 19, the junta forces came into Ou Chauk Lone Village, Kawlin Township, Sagaing Region, and took away 5 locals, including 16-year old Win Htike Naung. In the evening, they killed him. His body was found with broken legs and arms, and with a cracked skull and bruises on his face.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ခင်သိန်းမြင့်
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On July 20, a fight broke out between the junta forces and Cho Mai Mai coalition forces. The junta forces were coming Bant Bway Village, Yinmarbin Township, Sagaing Region, to resupply their troops. They then indiscriminately opened fire at those within the area. As a result, Khin Thein Myint from Kwae Chaung Village, Yinmarbin Township, was fatally shot while trying to flee to safety.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: အောင်အောင်
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On July 2, locals fled for their safety when junta forces launched an attack at Taung Pyauk Area, Thayetchaung Township, Tanintharyi Region. On July 7, a local named Aung Aung ran into the military convoy after going home to retrieve his belongings. He was shot and arrested, and he died on July 8.

A former National League for Democracy (NLD) member Hla Htoo from Mingalartaungnyunt Township, Yangon Region, was arrested at his house by the police and junta forces on July 23, at around 11:30 PM. He was arrested for allegedly supporting the People's Defense Forces, and on the morning of July 24, he died in the interrogation center from severe torture. The junta informed Hla Htoo's family members of his passing and cremated him, thus the family members were not able to see his body. Hla Htoo was physically healthy at the time of his arrest; and he was well known for his social charity work in Mingalartaungnyunt Trainstation Ward.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ခန့်ခန့်ငြိမ်း
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: At around 7 am on July 26, a military convoy carrying around 80 soldiers arrived near Magyee Oak Village, Khin-U Township, Sagaing Region, and opened fire. As a result, 14-year old Khant Khant Nyein was shot in his arm and chest. He had suffered severe wounds, so a local named Htay put Khant Khant Nyein and his mother in an ambulance that would transport them to the hospital. However, they ran into soldiers while trying to leave from the north side of the village, and were shot at. Htay died on the spot after being shot many times in his chest, thigh and pelvis; and Khant Khant Nyein died approximately 15 minutes later. The soldiers made his mother come out of the ambulance and lie down on the ground, and they then proceeded to kick her in the face. They also seized the ambulance.

Five villagers were killed and 20 local villagers were arrested by the armed wing of the Junta stationed at Yay Myein (South) Village, Salingyi Township, Sagaing Region. The junta troops had been stationed at the village since July 25. Later on, two villagers named Chit Shwe and Aung Moe living in Yay Myein (South) Village were found dead inside a house, and another villager named Aung Khaing was found with a gunshot injury. The names of the two other killed villagers has not yet been identified.

A local villager named Salai Mang Lian San was shot in the thigh and died due to severe bleeding. He had run into the soldiers whilst driving a motorbike to pick up and rescue children from the nursery school at the village.

On July 30 at around 2 am, Aye Kyaw, who is a video cameraman, living in Aung Chan Thar Village in Sagaing Township, Sagaing Region, was arrested at his home by military Division #33. cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: သက်နိုင်ဦး
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: Thet Naing Oo, a member of Twantay Royal Defence Force (TRDF) from Twantay Township, Yangon Region, was arrested by the junta soldiers in June. Thet Naing Oo died on July 28 from torture in interrogation. Following Thet Naing Oo's detention and torture, he suffered from various disease (hepatomegaly, kidney damage, hemorrhagic stroke, palsy, and coronary thrombosis). Junta forces sent Thet Naing Oo to Twantay Hospital for treatment, but there was no improvement. Thet Naing Oo died at Yangon General Hospital where he was sent for further treatment. The junta did not allow the family members to bury the dead body, instead the junta buried him at Htein Pin cemetery on July 29.

On July 31 at around 10 pm, Linn Aung, who is a member of Lamaing Youth Charity Group in Lamaing Town, Ye Township, Mon State, was shot dead by police. Linn Aung was shot when he ran into a junta patrol after arriving near Lamaing Naung Taw Gyi Pagoda while returning home from the charity office.

On July 29 at around 8 am, 8th Military Operations Command (MOC-8) from Peinnetaw Base fired seven artillery shells at Htee Nyar Lu Village in Min Lwin Village Tract, Thaton Township, Mon State. Artillery shells which exploded in that village killed a local named Naw Ka Paw Htoo and injured her daughter named Naw Htwe Htwe, as well as another villager named Tee Aung Zaya.

An artillery shell landed to the west of an IDP home in the area. A family member called Margaret, 13-years-old, was killed and her father seriously injured before dying the following day.

While seeking refuge, 17-year old Phyo Zayar Kyaw from Wet Ku Village, Saw Township, Magway Region, assisted his 16-year old friend Pyae Sone Tun return to his family. The pair were captured by hidden military scouts along the way in the forest and forced to reveal location of Phyo Zayar Kyaw's father. The father, called Nay Myo, was then found and assaulted by junta troops. Following this, they had beaten Phyo Zayar Kyaw to death in front of his father. They then took his body along with his friend Pyae Sone Tun, whilst Nay Myo was left behind.

On August 1, junta forces attacked Letpan Kyin Village, Myinmu Township in Sagaing Region, with 5 helicopters and raided the village. Then killing a villager called Htay Saung who was unwell, suffering from paralysis. While seeking refuge, he ran into a military convoy and was strangled to death with a towel.

On August 1, junta forces attacked Letpan Kyin Village, Myinmu Township in Sagaing Region, with 5 helicopters and raided the village. On August 6, they killed a villager called Naing Linn. After getting taken hostage, Naing Linn was shot in the back near Bawdi Tahtaung Pagoda and died.

On August 9, at around 8 PM, the junta forces dropped fire bombs from fighter planes at Sezin Village, Hpakant Township, Kachin State. As a result, houses were set on fire, and at around 9 PM the junta forces and Shanni Nationalities Army (SNA) came and re-set the village houses on fire. Additionally, locals died from the attack, amongst whom was 15-year-old Thiha who died during the bombing, as well as Thein Zaw, Kyaw Shi, San San Aye, Phoe Pein and Naing were shot dead.

On August 10, at around 10 AM, junta forces fired artillery shells indiscriminately, and one of them landed on a house in Hniarlawn Village, Hakha Township, Chin State. As a result, Pi Chia Hnem, who was cooking in the kitchen, died on the spot.

On August 7, at around 7:30 PM, Lwin Zaw Soe from Kanat Thiri Village, Kawthoung Township, Tanintharyi Region, was coming back home from work with his friend on a motorbike when the junta forces opened fire at them. They tried to turn around when they saw the junta forces at the Taw Win intersection in Aye Yate Nyain Ward, Kawthoung Township. However, Lwin Zaw Soe, who was in the backseat, fell down and when he tried to get up to run away, he was shot dead. His friend managed to escape.

In July, junta forces captured two GOD OF SNAKE (GOS) members, and forced them to act as guides for them; and on August 8, at around 6 AM, the junta forces were able to raid GOS's base in Thapyay Pin Su Village, Monywa Township, Sagaing Region. The two previously captured GOS members and one other GOS member were tortured and shot dead, with their bodies hid and buried under ground. The 3 members were Fatty, Thway Kyaw and David.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On August 9, at 8 PM, Sai Eaik Phwe from Tine Lone Village, Muse Township, Shan State, was leaving his home by motorbike when he was shot at indiscriminately by soldiers on the road near the entrance of the village. He suffered serious injuries, and although he was transported to hospital, he passed away. Moreover, his body has not be returned to his family yet.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On August 12, Ye Win Naing, a local villager, was torture to death by Junta soldiers who had raided and set fire to Shar Say Chat Village in Pauk Township, Magway Region. His injuries included having a severely beaten head, broken fingers, and pierced eyes.

On August 14, 7 youths from Wun Gyi Village, Khin-U Township, Sagaing Region were arrested in Shwebo Town on their way to work. Soon after they were shot dead by the junta forces near Ywar Thar Rest House. The victims' names were Kyaw Thu Hein, Nine Nine, Phyo Wai Soe, Min Ko, Min Nyi, Thura Tun and Zaw Hein.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: လင်းလင်းနိုင် (ခ) ငယ်လေး
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On August 8, at around 7 PM, the junta forces stationed at No.8 High School yard in San Myot Ward, Kale Township, Sagaing Region, opened fire when they saw a local named Linn Linn Naing (aka Nge Lay). Linn Linn Naing was on his way by motorbike to his relative's house for a sleepover with his friend when he was fatally shot.

On August 14, the junta forces raided and fired at Haing Hmarl Village, Tedim Township, Chin State with various weaponry. They set 8 households on fire and captured two siblings, 17-year old Lal Nun Puii and 15-year old Lal Ruat Mawia, who were at their house. The siblings were shot dead somewhere between Haing Hmarl and Ri Kaw Darl Town; and on August 16, their bodies were discovered.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ခိုင်ခိုင်ဝင်း
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: In the evening of August 11, the junta forces attacked Yin Paung Taing Village, Yinmarbin Township, Sagaing Region, and launched airstrikes with three Mi-35 fighter jets. This lasted for more than an hour, and then continued when some 60 soldiers were dropped from three helicopters to carry out a ground offensive, stationing themselves in the village on August 14. After the troops left, the bodies of 18 civilians, including a 12-year old child, were found in the village. Only 15 out of 18 deaths were identifiable and there were three children. The victims were 12-year-old Khaing Khaing Win, 13-year-old Aye Thuzar Nwel, 17-year-old Thaw Bhone Naing, Nwel Nwel Win, Saung Win Latt, Maung Myint, Nyein Thu Aung, Yin Myint, Kyaw Sein Win, Moe Moe, Zaw Win and Pwa Gyi. They had wounds inflicted by various weaponries. Khin Mya aged 82, and Ni aged 67, died of starvation as they hid in the village during the raid; while Kyaw Hmway died from respiratory issues while fleeing the junta attack.

The victims were 12-year-old Khaing Khaing Win, 13-year-old Aye Thuzar Nwel, 17-year-old Thaw Bhone Naing, Nwel Nwel Win, Saung Win Latt, Maung Myint, Nyein Thu Aung, Yin Myint, Kyaw Sein Win, Moe Moe, Zaw Win and Pwa Gyi. They had wounds inflicted by various weaponries. Khin Mya aged 82, and Ni aged 67, died of starvation as they hid in the village during the raid; while Kyaw Hmway died from respiratory issues while fleeing the junta attack.

On August 26, at around 6 AM, the junta column opened fire in a tea shop in Lel Zin Village, Monywa Township, Sagaing Region, injuring Aung Chit, who was drinking tea, in the leg. The junta column had 2 youths with them who were captured and forced to work as guides; however, they were severely beaten with sticks when they arrived at a school, and then killed. Afterwards, their bodies were burnt.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On August 24, at around 6:30 PM, two men coming back from work by motorbike were shot at by the junta forces on the road between Seik Nge Bridge and Pyidaw Thar Bridge, Myeik Township, Tanintharyi Region. Another victim, named Nyein Chan (aka Abdullah), was by the sidewalk and playing a game on his phone when he was hit by the bullets and killed; his body was returned to his family.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldHfL2UA8oU0Imne: Aung Zaw Oo (aka) Mohammed Pwa Ruk
cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: အောင်ဇော်ဦး (ခ) မိုဟာမက်ဖွာရူးက်
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On July 21, 2021, Aung Zaw Oo (aka Mohammed Pwa Ruk), a former political prisoner and activist, was arrested in Taunggyi Township, Shan State. And in May of 2022, he was sentenced to 7 year's imprisonment with charges under Counter-Terrorism Law Section 52(a). He had suffered from several broken ribs due to severe beatings in interrogation, and these injuries worsened while in prison. Although he was sent to Sao San Tun Hospital for treatment, he passed away on September 6, 2022.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: In the night of July 28, Long Awam (aka) Htlang Naw and his wife from Hpa Naing Village, Matupi Township, Chin State, were arrested by the junta forces, accusing them of having connection to Chinland Defense Force (Matupi). Afterwards, a case was made against him with 3 charges. The junta forces did not inform Long Awan's family about him getting killed during the interrogation on August 23, and instead only told them through the court, while also not returning his body to them. His wife was let go about a month ago, on the other hand.

As a result, one man was killed and another person was injured. The deceased was a resident of the ward; he was trying to run into a church when he heard the junta attacking, but was shot between the ribs and died.

On the morning of September 5, a column of the armed wing of the junta fired at and raided Maung Htaung Village, Budalin Township, Sagaing Region, with heavy weaponry. One of the artillery shells hit a local named Thin, killing her on the spot. Moreover, 2 women were injured.

On Apirl 8, Saw Baw Kaw and Saw Tar Thoo from Maw Phoe Klo Village, Maw Khee Village Tract, Kawkareik Township, Kayin State, were shot dead by the armed wing of the junta in Kwee Sar Phaw Village. During the attack, Saw Tar Thoo was driving a transport tractor loaded with items, and his wife and other villagers (including Saw Baw Kaw) were onboard. Saw Tar Too was shot in the chest twice, killing him on the spot; while Saw Baw Kaw was shot once in the stomach. Due to the soldiers not allowing to seek medical treatment,  Saw Baw Kaw died approximately 1 hour later. The soldiers returned their bodies to their families.

As a result, 56-year old local woman was hit by an artillery shell in the stomach and died instantly, while her husband was injured. Their house was also destroyed.

On September 12, at 5 pm, the armed wing of the junta launched an offensive into Zee Kone Village, Kawlin Township, Sagaing Region. Junta troops detained and then shot 2 local men dead. The deceased were a local Thein Zaw and a CDM school teacher Chan Thar.

On September 12, at 5 pm, the armed wing of the junta launched an offensive into Zee Kone Village, Kawlin Township, Sagaing Region. Junta troops detained and then shot 2 local men dead. The deceased were a local Thein Zaw and a CDM school teacher Chan Thar.

Zaw Myo Win (aka Ko Gyi) was arrested by the armed wing of the Junta in a house in Pyinoolwin at around 9 pm on September 12. Zaw Myo Win (aka Ko Gyi) was NLD Secretary of Oke Ta Ra Thi Ri Township in Nay Pyi Taw. He died less than 24 hours after detention, his dead body was not recovered by his family and was buried overnight under the pretext of COVID-19.  On the morning of September 13, the family of Zaw Myo Win (aka Ko Gyi) went to Pyinoolwin but did not see his body. The junta returned his phone, national identity card and other documents to his family.

One of the artillery shells exploded on Mway Taw Monastery in Mobye Town, resulting in the deaths of two sisters, who were 10 and 7 years-old, and 2 men aged 50-years-old. They were among people seeking refuge in the monastery and 13 others were seriously injured in the attack.

cellValuesByColumnId.fldtemYeWjXl02LvL: ခင်မျိုးနွယ်
cellValuesByColumnId.fldjrwtsuYe3r5QOW: On August 27, Khin Myo Nwel was detained by the armed wing of the Junta in Zee Phyu Kone Village, Twantay Township, Yangon Region. On August 29, junta forces reported to her family that she was dead. The junta did not mention cause of her death. On August 30, Khin Myo Nwel’s family went to Mingaladon Military Hospital, but only saw her face, the date of burial was unknown. Following shooting by junta forces, on the evening of August 22, near Zee Phyu Kone Village, about 50 locals were arrested, including Khin Myo Nwel, in Mya Goe and Mya Kan Thar villages, just outside Zee Phyu Kone Village.

On September 15, while Nyunt Win, the ward and village administrator for the National League for Democracy (NLD) party in Kanni Village, Inntakaw Township, Bago Region, was working in his own field, he was beaten and arrested by the armed wing of the Junta. His head was bleeding and was taken to the car. Then, he was tortured the interrogation by the LID 77. On September 16, the armed wing of the Junta reported to Nyut Win’s family about his death under the pretext of COVID-19. But his dead body was not recovered by his family and was burned immediately after. Nyunt Win was arrested and killed five days after returning to the village from hiding place.

On September 16, at around 4 am, the armed wing of the junta fired separate weaponry into Na Nwin Kaing  Village, from Kyauk Rik Base, Myaung Township, Sagaing Region. Kyi Tin who was seeking refuge in a monastery was killed by an artillery shell as a result.

On September 16, 13 civilians including students were killed when the armed wing of the junta raided Let Yet Kone Village in Tabayin Township, Sagaing Region. Junta forces fired heavy and light weaponry including air-strikes from two MI-35 aircraft at around 12 o’clock in the afternoon. In the airstrike, junta forces fired on the school where the students were learning in the yard of a village monastery, 4 students were killed on the spot. A further 20 people including teachers and severely injured students trapped in the school were arbitrarily detained and taken to Ye-U Township. Dead bodies of the children were packed with rice sacks, the bodies were not returned to the parents and instead cremated. According to the Ministry of Human Rights of the National Unity Government statement, Light Infantry Battalion 368 under the command of 10th Military Operation Command Headquarter committed the atrocity.
